      "notes": "Wife of the immigrant patriarch Wolphert (cp_fam_001). Death-date conflict between profile title (1658) and one snippet (\"after 1660\") — direct WikiTree-page verification pending. FOLLOW-UP: parents, birth place, exact death/burial dates. | KOUWENHOVEN 1997-1998 ENRICHMENT (cp_sou_043 / 044 / 045): Per Kemp 1995 archival research at Amersfoort (Notarieel Archief AT002b002 f. 282, 15 Dec 1611), Neeltgen's parents were JACOB PETERSZ + METGEN JACOBSDR (both deceased before 15 Dec 1611, Amersfoort). Siblings (per Kemp Table 1, Kouwenhoven 1998 p. 23): (i) HERMAN JACOBSZ (used surname Van Es / Nes; brewery worker, lived Leiden; m.1 Claesgen Jansdr 1607, d. 1615; m.2 Crijntgen Claesdr 1616, d. 1631; m.3 Trijntgen Paets Pietersdr 1632); (ii) AELTGEN JACOBS = Willem Dircx; (iii) PETER JACOBSZ (deceased 1612, daughter Petergen Petersdr underage 1611). All siblings + their issue remained in Netherlands. PATRONYMIC CONFIRMED as Jacobsdochter (NOT Jansdochter as De Boer 1912 misread / Cocheu 1939 propagated — see Kouwenhoven 1997 p. 217). Death year: Kouwenhoven 1998 Table 2 gives 'd. 1656' (consistent with Cocheu's 1656-12-06 lawsuit evidence already recorded in M death_date).\n\n## Naming pattern signals\n- Patronymic **Jacobsdr** (CONFIRMED by Kemp 1995 cp_sou_043) = daughter of Jacob Petersz. Brings 'Jacob' (her father's name) into the Cowenhoven name pool — son cp_fam_004 named for him.\n- Brings 'Pieter' (her grandfather's name, via Jacob Petersz = son of Peter) — son cp_fam_005 named in this pattern.\n- Sister Aeltgen Jacobs's name recurs as granddaughter cp_fam_064 (Aeltje Jacobs van Couwenhoven, b. 1645) — maternal-aunt naming pattern.\n- Brother Herman Jacobsz (Van Es / Nes) — surname did NOT propagate to American Cowenhovens.\n\n## Geographic timeline\n- ca. 1584 b. (presumed Amersfoort area; baptism not located)\n- by 1611-12-15 married Wolphert in Amersfoort, where they assumed her deceased parents' debts\n- 1611–1623 Amersfoort (named in multiple deeds with Wolphert)\n- 1625 emigrated to NA with Wolphert + 3 sons; mentioned by Patroon Kiliaen van Rensselaer in 1632 letter to Wolphert ('your wife was not much inclined' to move to Rensselaerswyck, VRBM 218 cp_sou_042)\n- 1625–1636 Manhattan (Bouwerie 3, then Bouwerie 6)\n- 1636+ New Amersfoort / Flatlands\n- d. before 1656-12-06 (per cp_fam_005 Pieter's injunction CDM 177; estate still 'not yet divided' on 1658-08-27 RNA 2:425)\n\n## Civic offices\n- (none — wife)\n\n## Kin network\n- Father **Jacob Petersz** (d. before 1611-12-15, Amersfoort) — Notarieel Archief AT002b002 f. 282\n- Mother **Metgen Jacobsdr** (d. before 1611-12-15, Amersfoort)\n- Brother **Herman Jacobsz** (used surname Van Es / Nes; b. Amersfoort, brewery worker Leiden 1607-13; granted Leiden citizenship 1613-12-19; carrier in The Unicorn brewery 1615-16): m.(1) Claesgen Jansdr 1607-09-08 d. 1615; m.(2) Crijntgen Claesdr 1616-07-23 d. 1631; m.(3) Trijntgen Paets Pietersdr 1632-10-10. Children: Pieter b.1608/09 d.1622/25; Jacob b.1612 'reported in West Indies 1636'; Machtelt b.1614/15 d.1622/25; Marijtgen + Claesge d. young; Claas b. 1622, m. Dirckgen Fransdr van Santen 1641-06-23 d. 1688-05-31.\n- Sister **Aeltgen Jacobs** = Willem Dircx (named alongside her in 1611 settlement document)\n- Brother **Peter Jacobsz** (d. 1612 Amersfoort) — daughter Petergen Petersdr underage in 1611\n- Husband Wolphert's brother **Willem Gerritsz Couwenhoven** had 5 sons; Wolphert was their court-appointed blood-guardian after Willem's death.\n- All NL kin remained in NL after Wolphert's family emigrated 1625; Cocheu and Kemp find no continuing correspondence.\n\n## RETROFIT NOTE (5/9 evening)\nNotes restructured under structured-comprehensive rule. Existing enrichment block preserved. ## sub-sections aggregate from cp_sou_042 / 043 / 044 / 045.",
