      "spouse_text": "1st: Hester (Symons) Sijmons / \"Daws\" (cp_fam_015) — m. 1640-12-02 New Amsterdam (she was widow of Jaques de Vernuis, from Amsterdam); 2nd: Aeltje Sybrants (cp_fam_023; WikiTree Sybrants-2, 1630-1689) — m. 1665-11-22 Reformed Dutch Church of New Amsterdam. Extramarital: Maria du Trieux (cp_fam_021; WikiTree Du_Trieux-45) bore his acknowledged daughter Aeltje du Trieux Pieters (cp_fam_022) per 1642-01-07 adoption document in the Dutch Manuscripts of New Amsterdam. | (3) UNCONFIRMED — Cocheu 70:4 (cp_sou_046) p. 355 reports 'some historians state that he m. (3) May 19, 1699, Josynthe Thomas'; not in MDC, no primary citation given; flag for further research, do NOT add to W related_family.",
      "children_summary": "Seven children per Wolfertszen-1 WikiTree list: with Maria du Trieux (extramarital) — Aeltje (du Trieux) Pieters (cp_fam_022), b. bef. 1642-01-07, acknowledged/adopted by Pieter; with Hester Simons (1st wife, INFERRED) — Petrus #1 (cp_fam_016, likely died young), Cornelius (cp_fam_017), Hester (cp_fam_018), Annetje (cp_fam_019, m. Anders Olafsson Stille by 1671), Aeltje Couwenhoven (cp_fam_020); with Aeltje Sybrants (2nd wife) — Petrus #2 (cp_fam_024; WikiTree Couwenhoven-72, b. 1665, bp. 1669-02-27 NYC RDC, d. 1705).",
      "is_enslaver": false,
      "enslaver_link": "",
      "sources": "WikiTree: https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Wolfertszen-1 (via WebSearch snippet 2026-04-24) | Kouwenhoven NYG&BR 128:4 (Oct 1997), pp. 209-218 (cp_sou_043) — 1640 New Amsterdam marriage record citing Pieter as bachelor 'from Amersfoort' | Cocheu NYG&BR 70:4 (Oct 1939), pp. 353-356 (cp_sou_046)",
      "notes": "Third of the three emigrant sons per Chris's ordering (Gerrit → Jacob → Pieter). Note: WikiTree-reported birth 1614 is actually EARLIER than Jacob's abt. 1615, so strict chronological birth-order would be Gerrit → Pieter → Jacob. Project ordering follows Chris's convention (2026-04-24). FOLLOW-UP: complete profile pull (spouse, children, marriage date); reconcile birth-order-vs-project-order question if consequential. | 2026-04-24 UPDATE: Pieter family block added (cp_fam_015-024): two wives Hester Simons + Aeltje Sybrants, extramarital mother Maria du Trieux, and seven children. WikiTree lists two \"Petrus Couwenhoven\" entries — treated as #1 died young (cp_fam_016, stub) and #2 (cp_fam_024 = Couwenhoven-72, b. 1665) per standard Dutch naming practice. Mother attribution for 5 of Hester Simons's children is INFERRED from marriage timeline (Hester m. 1640; Aeltje Sybrants m. 1665; most children dated in the intervening window) — not confirmed per child. \"Lieutenant\" rank cited by secondary genealogy (Geni) awaits primary-source verification. | KOUWENHOVEN 1997 ENRICHMENT (cp_sou_043 fn 14, NYG&BR 128:4 p. 211): Pieter's 1st marriage is recorded in Marriages from 1639 to 1801 in the Reformed Dutch Church, New Amsterdam · New York City (NYG&BS Colls. 9, 1940), p. 10: 'Pieter Wolfertsen, j.m. [jonge man = bachelor] from Amersfoort, married Hester Simons on 2 December 1640.' Confirms Pieter's pre-emigration origin in Amersfoort, Utrecht, Netherlands. Notable consequence: rules out Beernink's 1916 claim that a 'Peter Wulphersen' resident of Hoogland married Jannitje Cornelis at Amersfoort 11 Apr 1639 — Kouwenhoven 1997 fn 14 shows that Hoogland Peter was a different person, not our cp_fam_005 (who was already in New Netherland by 1640).\n\n## Naming pattern signals\n- **Pieter** = patrilineal-uncle pattern (his maternal grandfather's father per Cocheu line); recurs heavily in his line (cp_fam_016 Petrus #1, cp_fam_024 Petrus #2, descendants Peter #87 cp_fam_087, etc.).\n- 1st wife Hester Symons brings **Hester** — recurs as daughter cp_fam_018 Hester Pieterse, granddaughter cp_fam_090 Hester Peterse.\n- 2nd wife Aeltje Sibrants brings **Aeltje / Altie** — though daughter Aeltje #15 = cp_fam_022 was actually the natural daughter of Maria du Trieux, NOT Aeltje Sibrants (cp_sou_046 #15 KCo 79).\n- Pieter's children show notable ANGLICIZATION pattern (Peter, John, David, Hester, Mary in grandson cp_fam_024's line) — consistent with Pieter-branch's NJ migration → Conover surname adoption.\n\n## Geographic timeline\n- ca. 1614 b. Amersfoort (per Kouwenhoven 1998 Table 2 cp_sou_045)\n- 1625 emigrated NA with parents at age ~11\n- 1640-12-02 m.(1) Hester Symons RDC NA\n- early career: mercantile pursuits in partnership with brother Jacob (Jacob also a miller in flour trade); Pieter ended partnership when Jacob's speculations failed (cp_sou_046)\n- engaged in brewing — business at corner of Whitehall and Pearl Streets, NY (VM 1862:764 cp_sou_046)\n- 1663-06-26 to 1663-12-15+ Esopus war: lieutenant under Captain Martin Krigier; commanded two yachts on Hudson 1663-10-15; treaty witness/interpreter 1664-05-15\n- 1665 wife Hester Symons d., buried NY\n- 1665-11-22 m.(2) Aeltje Sibrants (cp_fam_023; MDC 31)\n- post-1665 principally at farmhouse Elizabethtown, NJ (NY house on Pearl St near Whitehall retained)\n- 1699-05-19 (per Cocheu 'some historians') possible m.(3) Josynthe Thomas — UNCONFIRMED\n- living 1700 (workbook prior); per Cocheu 71:1 still alive when his son Peter Peterse cp_fam_024's death-window opens 1700\n\n## Civic offices\n- 1653-02-02 Schepen of New Amsterdam on the first board (Stokes Iconography 6:643 cp_sou_046)\n- 1653-03-15 committee for security of City\n- 1655-10-18 orphan-master\n- 1656-02-25 one of two judges of Orphans' Court\n- 1657-12-15 fire buckets to hang at his house\n- 1659-02-07 resigned Orphans' Court\n- 1662-03-10 again orphan-master\n- 1663-06-26 resigned as Schepen to join Cregier's company as lieutenant; oath of office 1663-06-20\n- 1663-06-30 member of council of war; goes to Esopus Kill with troops\n- 1663-08-27 sends soldiers to Harlem and other villages\n- 1663-10-15 in command of two yachts on Hudson\n- 1663-11-21 / 1664-03-15 negotiator with Wappingers + Esopus Indians for peace\n- 1664-05-15 witness + interpreter at signing of treaty between many tribes' Sachems and Dutch\n- 1665-05-02 complains of billeting assessment\n- 1666-04-03 elected city surveyor\n- Total Schepen tenure: 6 years (Cocheu 70:4 framing)\n\n## Kin network\n- 1st wife **Hester Symons (Daws)** cp_fam_015, widow of Jaques de Vernuis van Amsterdam; d. 1660 (per Cocheu 70:4 MDC 10).\n- 2nd wife **Aeltje Sibrants** cp_fam_023; m. 1665-11-22 RDC NY MDC 31.\n- Possible 3rd wife Josynthe Thomas 1699-05-19 — UNCONFIRMED.\n- Natural daughter **Aeltje du Trieux Pieters** cp_fam_022 by Maria du Trieux cp_fam_021 (acknowledged via 1642-01-07 court adoption document).\n- 5 legitimate children with Hester Symons + 1 with Aeltje Sibrants (cp_fam_024 Petrus #2): cp_fam_016/_017/_018/_019/_020/_022/_024.\n- Brothers cp_fam_003 Gerret + cp_fam_004 Jacob — Pieter brought the 1656-12-06 lawsuit against execution of judgment vs Jacob to protect father Wolphert (CDM 177; RNA 2:425, cp_sou_042). On 1658-08-27 (when Pieter himself was Schepen) he again testified mother's property 'is not yet divided' (RNA 2:425).\n\n## RETROFIT NOTE (5/9 evening)\n## sub-sections from cp_sou_042 + cp_sou_046 + cp_sou_043. | 2026-05-18 ENRICHMENT (cp_famsou_025 1646 Gerrit estate settlement): named as \"Piter Wolphersen, brother of the aforesaid Gerrit Wolphersen, deceased\" — joint guardian (first party) of deceased brother Gerrit's 4 children (cp_fam_007-010) alongside father cp_fam_001 Wolphert + brother cp_fam_004 Jacob. Signed as \"Pieter Wolfersen.\" Confirms his role as Couwenhoven family member at age ~32.",
