      "sources": "Pelletreau, W. S., Abstracts of Wills on File in the Surrogate's Office, City of New York, Liber 3-4, p. 164 (NYHS Collections) | FamilySearch viewer: https://www.familysearch.org/library/books/viewer/140706/?offset=0#page=172 | Original probate: Liber 4, p. 140, proved at Court of Records, City Hall, NY, 1689/90; letters of admin to wife Sarah 1690-02-07; entered 1690-11-08 (Clerk Abraham Gouverneur); signed at Nortwyck 1689-07-18; witnesses Jacob Groot and Wolfert Webber | WikiTree: https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Kouwenhoven-31 (via WebSearch snippet 2026-04-24; page not fetched directly — wikitree.com redirects to www. which is off the cowork allowlist) | Cocheu NYG&BR 71:1 (Jan 1940), pp. 69-74 (cp_sou_047)",
      "notes": "RENUMBERED 2026-04-24 from cp_fam_006 → cp_fam_012 to insert the Gerrit-family block (cp_fam_006-010) and Hester (cp_fam_011) ahead of the Johanes branch. Mother Parent|cp_fam_011 link added (previously no mother link; only father was known). | RENUMBERED 2026-04-24 from cp_fam_001 → cp_fam_006 to make space for the immigrant patriarch line (cp_fam_001-005) at the top of the sheet. | Pelletreau's abstract reads 'anno 1690, the 17th day of June' in the body but the actum/signing line reads '18 July, 1689' and letters of admin were granted 1690-02-07 — the body 1690 is almost certainly a transcription error for 1689. Different branch from cp_ens_002-004: Kouwenhoven-31 is on the Jacob-Wolphertse (Manhattan) line; cp_ens_002-004 descend from Willem Gerritsz (Brooklyn/Monmouth). Both trace to immigrant Wolphert Gerritsz (WikiTree Gerritsz-51, 1630 to New Netherland). Title 'Secretary' = colonial notarial office, useful for disambiguation from contemporary Johannes/Jans in the extended family. FOLLOW-UP: consult full probate (Liber 4, p. 140) — will abstract is silent on enslaved people but a Nortwyck landholder of his standing in 1689 NYC plausibly owned enslaved labor; if named, reclassify enslaver_status + spawn UNNAMED/EVENT rows.\n\n## Naming pattern signals\n- First Jan / Johannes in the Jacob branch (Wolphert's mother-in-law's father was 'Jacob Petersz' — no Jan in immediate ancestry, but Jan was a common Dutch given name).\n- His children: Jacob, Francois (twice), Hester, Lysbeth, Jacomyntie, Johannes, Maria, Catalyntie, Pieter — French-Huguenot tinge ('Francois') from wife's Saartje Frans 'from Harlem' background possibly.\n\n## Geographic timeline\n- 1641-05-11 b. New Amsterdam\n- High Street, NY City (residence)\n- 1689 served on Gov. Leisler's Council\n- between 1690-06-17 and 1690-11-18 d. NY\n\n## Civic offices\n- 1689 Member, Governor Leisler's Council\n- Member, Court of Exchequer\n- Secretary 'between ye Limits of Harlem and Bowery' (RNA 6:401; KCo 79; Van Rensselaer Hist. of City of NY 2:434)\n\n## Kin network\n- Wife Saertje Frans 'from Harlem' (later remarried 1692-11-03 Jan Byvangk widower of Belitie Duyckinck).\n- 10 children all bp. DRC NY — strongly Manhattan-anchored sub-line of the Jacob branch.\n\n## COCHEU 71:1 ENRICHMENT (cp_sou_047)\nTightened birth from 'bef. 1641' to 1641-05-11. Death-window CONFLICT with prior 'Couenhovens and Kinsfolk' source — Cocheu 71:1 WNYHS 1:163 citation preferred; conflict flagged for primary verification.",
