      "occupation": "",
      "father_text": "Johanes Van Cowenhoven (cp_fam_012)",
      "mother_text": "Saartie Frans (cp_fam_013)",
      "spouse_text": "Anna Resmen (alias Emerson, Remmers, Remmerson) of Gravesend LI. m. Newtown 1685-07-07 by Justice Morgan Jones. Joined RDC NY 1717-05-27 + Hackensack Ch. NJ 1718 by letter (KCo 78). NOTE: Cocheu 71:3 states Gravesend Ch. records say parents were married at Gravesend — possible record discrepancy.",
      "children_summary": "5 children per Cocheu 71:3 #238-242: (238) Johannes⁶ bp. Flatbush 1685-08-16 (Flatb 137), d.y. — NOT MINTED; (239) Jannetje⁶ — said to have m. Hendrick Bennett of Gowanus LI [Cocheu has 'GRAVE DOUBTS', see note below]; (240) Neeltje⁵ — said to have m. Abraham Vanderwater of Gowanus [DOUBTS]; (241) Saartje⁵ — said to have m. Isaac Vanderwater [DOUBTS]; (242) cp_fam_154 Johannes⁶ bp. NY 1696-03-08 (BDC 234), m. Lucretia Luyster (TDC). Per Chris (5/9 late session): #239/240/241 NOT MINTED — see note for the Cornelius #23 alternative hypothesis.",
      "is_enslaver": false,
      "enslaver_link": "",
      "sources": "Pelletreau, W. S., Abstracts of Wills on File in the Surrogate's Office, City of New York, Liber 3-4, p. 164 — named as eldest son; to receive 100 guilders before any division; given a lot in the Pasture-land 1685 (10-yr agreement; built house and barn); father had one new iron-work wagon made for him | WikiTree Kouwenhoven-31 children list (via WebSearch snippet 2026-04-24) — birth date 30 Nov 1664 | Cocheu NYG&BR 71:1 (Jan 1940), pp. 69-74 (cp_sou_047) — Cocheu 71:1 confirms parentage cp_fam_012 + cp_fam_013, bp. 1664-11-30 BDC 75, m. Newtown 1685-07-07 Anna Remerson of Gravesend KCo 79 | Cocheu NYG&BR 71:3 (Jul 1940), pp. 273-276 (cp_sou_049)",
      "notes": "RENUMBERED 2026-04-24 from cp_fam_008 → cp_fam_014. | RENUMBERED 2026-04-24 from cp_fam_003 → cp_fam_008. | STUB — full row pending own WikiTree profile lookup. Patronymic 'Jansen' (= son of Jan/Johannes) confirms him as son of cp_fam_001. Classic Dutch naming pattern: eldest son named for paternal grandfather — independently supports the cp_fam_001 father-Jacob hypothesis (paternal grandfather = Jacob Wolphertse). FOLLOW-UP: disambiguate this Jacob from contemporaneous Jacobs in the broader family (Jacob Willemse van Couwenhoven, 1679-1744, Van_Couwenhoven-70, is a DIFFERENT Jacob on the Willemse line). Find WikiTree profile.\n\n## SOURCE-NAME ENRICHMENT (cp_sou_049 — Cocheu NYG&BR 71:3)\n- Marriage Newtown 1685-07-07 by Justice Morgan Jones (KCo 79) — civil marriage, not church.\n- Couple joined RDC NY 1717 + Hackensack NJ 1718 by letter — geographic relocation NY→NJ ca. 1717-1718.\n\n## Cocheu's 'grave doubts' on alleged daughters #239/240/241 (Jannetje, Neeltje, Saartje)\nCocheu 71:3 (cp_sou_049) p. 275 reproduces the conventional attribution — Jannetje m. Hendrick Bennett of Gowanus LI, Neeltje m. Abraham Vanderwater of Gowanus, Saartje m. Isaac Vanderwater (twins b. 1697-09-05 sons of Peter Jansen Vanderwater + Marie Christien); the last three couples settled Monmouth Co. NJ — but EXPRESSES GRAVE DOUBTS.\nAlternative hypothesis (cited by Cocheu): Abraham Van Deventer's will dated 1733-04-25, pro. 1733-12-11 (NJWills 2:496) names father-in-law CORNELIUS COWNOVER. Van Doorn Gen. (1909) p. 425 says Isaac Van Deventer (bp. 1704, of Hunterdon Co. NJ + VA) m. Saartje Couwenhoven (sister of Altje, who m. brother Abraham). Both Aeltje + Saartje are claimed to be daughters of CORNELIUS (No. 23) COUWENHOVEN (= cp_fam_017 Cornelius Pieterse) + Margaretta Schenck — NOT daughters of Jacob #67.\nCocheu calls for primary records to clarify. Per Chris's 5/9 late-session decision: NOT MINTING #239/240/241 as cp_fam rows; preserve the data in this note + cross-reference on cp_fam_017. Defer mints until primary archival evidence settles which Cornelius is correct.\n\n## Geographic timeline\n- 1664-11-30 bp. NY (BDC 75)\n- 1685-07-07 m. Newtown LI by Justice Morgan Jones (cp_pla_067)\n- 1685-1717 likely Brooklyn / Gravesend area (children's bp. records)\n- 1717-05-27 joined RDC NY\n- 1718 joined Hackensack Ch. NJ by letter — relocated to Hackensack Bergen Co. NJ\n- d. after 1718; exact date/place unknown\n\n## Civic offices\n- (none documented in 71:3)\n\n## Kin network\n- 1718 Hackensack relocation = early Cowenhoven anchor in Bergen Co. NJ. Possibly relevant to later Bergen-branch enslaver attribution work (cp_ens_001 Judge Nicholas + Case 37536 master + cp_per_138/139 Master). Worth checking if his line continues in Hackensack church/civil records.\n- Wife Anna Resmen of Gravesend brings Resmen/Emerson surname into kin-network.\n- Son cp_fam_154 Johannes m. Lucretia Luyster — Luyster cousin link with cp_fam_026's daughter cp_fam_149 Jacomyntie m. Elbert Luyster.",
      "raw_related_family": "Parent|cp_fam_012;Parent|cp_fam_013;Sibling|cp_fam_079;Sibling|cp_fam_080;Sibling|cp_fam_081;Sibling|cp_fam_082;Sibling|cp_fam_083;Sibling|cp_fam_084;Sibling|cp_fam_085;Sibling|cp_fam_086;Child|cp_fam_154;Spouse|Anna Resmen",
