      "spouse_text": "Margaretta Schenck (cp_fam_308) b. 1678-01-16; m. 1700-09-03 Flatlands LI (date questionable per Cocheu — 1st child bp. 1700-09-08); d. 1751-12-06 Pleasant Valley NJ.",
      "children_summary": "14 children per Cocheu #23 (EDSM 25–26): 13 named, all minted as cp_fam_101–113 (William, Annetje, Neeltje, Roelof, Altje, Jannetje, Sarah, Leah, Maria, Rachel, Margaretta, Jacometje, Caterina); #134 unnamed bp. 1724-10-25 FM (not mintable).",
      "is_enslaver": true,
      "evidence_status": "documented",
      "enslaver_link": "cp_ens_004",
      "sources": "WikiTree: https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Couwenhove-2 | Son profile Couwenhove-3 (Willem Cornelis Couwenhoven, 1700–1755).; New Jersey, U.S., Abstract of Wills, 1670-1817 [database online]. Provo, UT: Ancestry.com Operations, Inc., 2011. Original: New Jersey State Archives. New Jersey, Published Archives Series, First Series, Volume XXX, Abstracts of Wills, 1730-1750. Trenton, NJ: John L. Murphy Publishing Company. Will of Cornelius Couwenhoven (Covenhoven), Middletown Township, Monmouth Co., yeoman, dated 1735-11-22; proved 1736-06-22. Lib. C, p. 107. Ancestry collection: https://www.ancestry.com/search/collections/2793/; existing Active rows 87-91 (cp_per_092-096) source: https://www.ancestry.com/search/collections/2793/records/16187 (Hannah, indexed record).",
      "notes": "Older brother of Albert Willemse Couwenhoven (cp_ens_002); same father (Willem Gerritsz, Couwenhoven-4 = cp_fam_007). Three-brothers cluster confirmed 2026-04-25: Cornelis (this row), Albert (cp_ens_002), and Jacob (cp_ens_009) are the three sons of cp_fam_007 who all settled Monmouth Co. NJ as enslaving yeomen.\n\nSchenck-sister marriage MATCH: wife Margaretta and Albert's wife Neeltje Roelofse are both daughters of Roelof Martense Schenck + Annetje Pieterse Wyckoff (Cocheu #7 + #23 + #43; WikiTree Couwenhove-2 snippet 2026-04-24). Schenck parents queued to Mint_Queue.md as Tier-1 Schenck/Wyckoff candidates.\n\nHYPOTHESIS — cp_rec_003 'William Kowenhoven of Corroway' likely = eldest son Willem Cornelis Couwenhoven (cp_fam_101, Couwenhove-3, 1700–1755): 1755 death year matches, and brother Roelof (cp_fam_104) matches the 'Roleph Cownover' brother named in cp_rec_003. If confirmed, cp_rec_003 should cross-ref to cp_ens_004 instead of cp_rec_001. Strengthened by 1735 will (cp_eve_014) confirming William eldest + Roelof as named legatees. Formal cross-ref upgrade DEFERRED to separate pass.\n\nBirth date open question per Cocheu_Print_Errors_Master.md #2: Cocheu prints 'b. Nov. 20, 1672' AND 'd. May 16, 1736, ae. 64-5-17' which are internally inconsistent. Stone-math (64y 5m 17d on d. 1736-05-16) implies DOB ≈ 1671-11-29. Workbook prior 1672-09-29 was a secondary derivation (KCo & NJMis). Per Chris 2026-05-22 reviewing under cp_ens_004 pass: applying Cocheu printed 1672-11-20 pending Schenck-Couwenhoven Cem gravestone walk to definitively close.\n\n1735 will (cp_eve_014, NJWills 2:115) bequeathed 5 enslaved people: Hannah ('the old negro woman', cp_per_092) → wife Margaret; Sam (cp_per_093) + Tom (cp_per_094) → eldest son William; James (cp_per_095) + Toney (cp_per_096) → son Roeloffe. Will-witness Gerret Schenck likely Margaretta's brother (Schenck kin-network reinforcement). 11 daughters of William + Roeloffe named in will: Leah, Catherine, Yacominekey, Margaret, Rachel (via William); Mary, Sarah, Neelkye, Allkye, Yannikee, Anne (via Roeloffe).\n\nNaming pattern: Schenck-route names heavy in children — Roelof (after wife's father), Margaretta (after wife), Sarah (Schenck-side), Annetje (after wife's mother Annetje Pieterse Wyckoff — maternal-grandmother naming). Patrilineal core retained: William, Cornelis (presumed), Jan (cousin-husband Schenck), Maria, Caterina, Rachel, Jacometje, Leah.\n\nCocheu 71:1 (cp_sou_047) records intra-family cousin marriage with cp_fam_009 chain: wife Margarieta Schenck is granddaughter of Cornelis's aunt cp_fam_009 via Roelof Schenck's 1st marriage (Neeltje Gerretse). One of 4 such cousin marriages among Willem cp_fam_007's children (siblings #23/#24/#25/#26 = cp_ens_004 / cp_ens_071 / cp_ens_072 / cp_ens_073).\n\nStage 2 cleanup 2026-05-22 (cp_ens_004 Cocheu Discrepancy Review): spouse-field bloat extracted (parents-of-spouse → cp_fam_308); will-dated content moved to will_probate; 13 Child| edges written to related_enslavers (reverse Parent|cp_ens_004 verified on cp_fam_101-113; cp_fam_103 received missing reciprocal); cp_eve_014 added to notable_records; cp_eve_014.place_id set to cp_pla_023; birth_date applied per Chris's Cocheu-printed decision.",
      "raw_related_family": "",
      "raw_related_enslavers": "Sibling|cp_ens_002; Sibling|cp_ens_009; Sibling|cp_fam_057; Spouse|cp_fam_308; Child|cp_fam_101; Child|cp_fam_102; Child|cp_fam_103; Child|cp_fam_104; Child|cp_fam_105; Child|cp_fam_106; Child|cp_fam_107; Child|cp_fam_108; Child|cp_fam_109; Child|cp_fam_110; Child|cp_fam_111; Child|cp_fam_112; Child|cp_fam_113; Father|cp_fam_007; Mother|cp_fam_061",
      "notable_records": "1735-11-22 will (Lib. C, p. 107; proved 1736-06-22) bequeathing 5 enslaved people: Hannah (\"the old negro woman\", cp_per_092) → wife Margaret with all estate; Sam (cp_per_093) and Tom (cp_per_094) → eldest son William (= Willem Cornelis Couwenhoven, Couwenhove-3, 1700-1755), with 156 acres from William Bowne (1704+1705) + 120 acres from Daniel Hendricks/John Schenck/Garrat Schenck/Peter Weycoff (1716); James (cp_per_095) and Toney (cp_per_096) → son Roeloffe (= Roelof Cornelisse Couwenhoven), with residue of land + meadow + 2½ acres from James and Rachel Hubbard (1706) + 2 acres from Jonathan Holmes (1719) + 10 acres from John Bowne (1703) + 125 acres from Garrat and John Schenck (1700). Executors: wife Margaret + sons William and Roeloffe. Witnesses: Gerret Schenck (likely brother-in-law via wife's Schenck family), Johannis Bennet, Robert Dodsworth. EVENT cp_eve_014.",
      "enslaved_people_linked": "cp_per_092; cp_per_093; cp_per_094; cp_per_095; cp_per_096",
