      "enslaver_link": "cp_fam_054",
      "sources": "WikiTree Couwenhoven-24 (https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Couwenhoven-24); Rootsweb Conover descendants chart (https://sites.rootsweb.com/~conover/Pages/newinfor.htm — \"Willem sold his Flatlands property to his son William on November 1, 1709\"); Gerret Willemse Kouwenhoven 1777 Will p.5 — primary genealogical statement: \"all my Patentees Right in the Common & undivided Land and meadows in the Township of flatlands which my father William Kouwenhoven Did make over to me which he had Received from his father willem Garrites [Gerritse] Van Kouwenhoven by a Certain Instrument in Writing Bearing Date the twenty Eight Day of July one thousand Seven hundred and twenty Seven\" (NYSA J0038-92 SS2 2869). | Cocheu NYG&BR 71:1 (Jan 1940), pp. 69-74 (cp_sou_047) — Cocheu 71:1 confirms parentage cp_fam_007 + cp_fam_061, b. 1686-03-07 d. 1769-01-19, m. 1709-06-05 Annetie Lucasse Van Voorhees | Cocheu NYG&BR 71:3 (Jul 1940), pp. 273-276 (cp_sou_049)",
      "notes": "INTERMEDIATE LINEAGE NODE — minted 2026-04-26 from grandson Gerret's 1777 will primary-source statement of the cp_fam_007 → cp_fam_054 → cp_ens_027 transfer chain. Father cp_fam_007 sold his Flatlands property to this son on 1709-11-01 (per Rootsweb) and later retired to NJ; this son passed the Patentee Right + property to his son Gerret cp_ens_027 on 28 July 1727 by written instrument (per Gerret's own 1777 will text page 5). The 28 July 1727 instrument should still be findable in Flatlands town records or family papers if preserved — FOLLOW-UP. CHRIS-DESCENDANT NOTE: this is a direct Flatlands-line ancestor on the cp_fam_007 sub-branch that stayed in Flatlands rather than migrating to Monmouth NJ (cf. cp_ens_002 Albert Willemse / cp_ens_004 Cornelis Willemse — Albert and Cornelis are siblings of Willem Willemse who migrated, while Willem Willemse stayed Flatlands and inherited the home property). Surname spelling: \"Kowenhoven\" / \"Kouwenhoven\" without R per feedback_kouwenhoven_no_r.md.\n\n## SOURCE-NAME ENRICHMENT (cp_sou_049 — Cocheu NYG&BR 71:3 Jul 1940 pp. 273-276)\n- Will dated 1757-12-10, pro. 1769-03-30 (WNYHS 7:243); names deceased father, wife, children, sons-in-law and grandchildren; refers to slaves and lands in Flatlands. Will text is enslavement evidence — flag for cross-reference with EVENT sheet during Stage 2 will-cluster harvest.\n- Wife Annetie Voorhees: parents Lucas Stevense Van Voorhees + Catherine Hansen Van Noortstrand. Brings Voorhees patronymic into the Willem-Willemse line.\n\n## Naming pattern signals\n- 5 of 12 children carry mother's-line names (Catalina, Catryntje, Annetje recurring) — Voorhees/Van Noortstrand naming influence.\n- 3 sons named William/Willem (one d.y. 1710, one of NJ b.1713, plus the namesake in cp_ens_027 Garret line). Willem first-name density confirms Wolphert > Gerrit > Willem patriline.\n- Daughter Catalina (#182) and Catryntje (#188) likely named for maternal grandmother Catherine Hansen Van Noortstrand.\n\n## Geographic timeline\n- 1686-03-07 b. Flatlands LI\n- 1709-06-05 m. Flatbush DRC\n- ca. 1709-1769 resided Flatlands LI throughout (children's births recorded Flatlands; will refers to Flatlands lands)\n- 1769-01-19 d. Flatlands; bur. Flatlands Cemetery (cp_pla_066)\n\n## Civic offices\n- (none documented in 71:3; will-bearer slave-owner only)\n\n## Kin network\n- 4 of his 12 children married into Schenck family (cp_fam_141 m. Margaretta #234, cp_fam_142 m. Gerret #233, cp_fam_145 m. John #235, cp_fam_146 m. Albert #236). These Schencks (sequentially Cocheu-numbered #233-236, likely siblings) are presumed descendants of cp_fam_009 Neeltje Gerrits' Schenck line — making 4 cousin marriages back into the Cowenhoven cluster. DEFER Schenck mints until Cocheu provides their genealogy directly (likely 71:4+).\n- cp_fam_147 Neeltje⁶ m. John Duryea (Duryea cluster anchor — Flatlands).\n- cp_fam_144 Altje⁶ m. Cornelius Voorhees (continues mother's Voorhees line).\n- cp_ens_027 Garret⁶ m. Antie Lefferts (Lefferts cluster Flatlands).\n\n## PROMOTED FROM FAMILY (2026-05-10 single-sheet migration)\nEvidence: Willem Willemse Kowenhoven — will text is enslavement evidence (cp_sou_049 Cocheu 71:3)\nOriginal enslaver_status field: Unknown (no surviving will or probate inventory of his own located yet; pending NYSA / Kings Co. probate index search 1769)",
