      "spouse_text": "Elizabeth — (surname unknown). She survived him + executed his estate (Account Feb. 5, 1730/1 'by Elizabeth Covenoven, Execx.')",
      "children_summary": "6 children per Cocheu 71:4 #282-287 (all minted as cp_fam Gen 5 Pieter branch NJ Great Egg Harbor cluster): (282) cp_fam_174 Peter5; m. Katherine —. (283) cp_fam_175 Isaiah5; m. Sara Dusenberry. (284) cp_fam_176 Thomas5. (285) cp_fam_177 Micajah5; m. Deborah Stanton. (286) cp_fam_178 Mary5. (287) cp_fam_179 Judith5.",
      "is_enslaver": false,
      "enslaver_link": "",
      "sources": "Cocheu NYG&BR 71:1 (Jan 1940), pp. 69-74 (cp_sou_047) | Cocheu NYG&BR 71:4 (Oct 1940), pp. 365-367 (cp_sou_050) | Cocheu NYG&BR 83:3 (Jul 1952), pp. 147-156 (cp_sou_058)",
      "notes": "Cocheu 71:1 (cp_sou_047) #87. NJ Conover-line descendant. Will dated 1730-06-26 pro. 1730-08-21 NJ Wills 2:116.\n\n## SOURCE-NAME ENRICHMENT (cp_sou_050 — Cocheu NYG&BR 71:4 #87)\nPieter-branch outpost in Great Egg Harbor NJ — coastal Atlantic Co. Distinct from the Gerrit-branch Marlborough/Middletown cluster.\nWill 1730-06-26 / pro 1730-08-21 (NJWills 2:116). Wife Elizabeth was Executrix.\n\n## Naming pattern signals\n- 'Isaiah', 'Micajah', 'Thomas', 'Judith' = Old-Testament-heavy English-Quaker-style naming pattern (very different from the Dutch RDC pattern of Pleasant Valley Cowenhovens). Suggests influence of NJ Anglo-Protestant neighbors (Stanton surname in #285 = English/Quaker).\n- Possible religious shift Reformed Dutch → Quaker / Baptist / Anglican in the Great Egg Harbor branch.\n\n## SOURCE-NAME ENRICHMENT (cp_sou_058 — Cocheu NYG&BR 83:3 #87)\nCocheu 83:3 (cp_sou_058) #87 — substantial enrichment of this stub row:\n\n## Will + estate\n- Will dated 1730-06-26 / proved 1730-08-21 (NJA:23:108). Mentioned wife, four sons, and two daughters.\n- Executors: wife Elizabeth + brother John (cp_fam_088).\n- Witnesses: Samuel Huested and John Watts.\n- Wife Elizabeth a \"Quakeress of Great Egg Harbour\" — first documented Quaker influence on the Pieter branch. Likely suppressed enslavement in this lineage.\n\n## Civic offices + land\n- Collector for Great Egg Harbor Township 1718 AND 1720 (Glou. Co. 2nd Ct. rec. Bk. p.83).\n- One of original surveys on Absecon Beach (now Atlantic City), 100 acres, dated 1729-05-20 (A. L. English, Hist. of Atlantic City, 1884, p.16).\n\n## Naming-pattern signal\n- 6 children named: Peter (continued line), Isaiah, Thomas, Micajah, Mary, Judith. Introduction of distinctively Quaker-influenced names (Isaiah, Micajah) marks this branch's divergence from the patrilineal Wolphert > Gerrit > Jan > Peter naming pattern.",
      "raw_related_family": "Parent|cp_fam_024;Sibling|cp_fam_088;Sibling|cp_fam_089;Sibling|cp_fam_090;Sibling|cp_fam_091;Spouse|Elizabeth —;Child|cp_fam_174;Child|cp_fam_175;Child|cp_fam_176;Child|cp_fam_177;Child|cp_fam_178;Child|cp_fam_179",
