      "occupation": "Yeoman (per will text — testator self-styled \"yeoman\")",
      "father_text": "Peter Van Couwenhoven (cp_fam_034 = Cocheu #216, b. 1713 Brooklyn d. 1786-1788 Somerset Co NJ; m. Elizabeth Debevoise daughter of Joost Debevoise + Mary Remsen) - PRIMARY MATCH per Cocheu 82:4 #661 (cp_sou_057).",
      "mother_text": "Elizabeth Debevoise (daughter of Joost & Mary Remsen Debevoise; predeceased husband Peter by 1765 per father Joost Debevoise's 1765-05-01 will WNYHS:8:100-01).",
      "spouse_text": "Catharine Suydam (cp_fam_357, minted 2026-05-30; b. ~1737, d. 1815-04-22 in her 78th year per Cocheu 82:4 #661; daughter of Cornelius Suydam per his 1768-12-12 will NJA:34:513 mentioning \"daughter Catharine, wife of Nicholas Covenhoven\"). m. ~1758. Both Nicholas and Catharine bur. Garretsen Farm near Bound Brook NJ. **CORRECTION 2026-05-10**: prior workbook field \"Unnamed widow\" superseded by Cocheu 82:4 #661 primary citation.",
      "children_summary": "Per 1802 will (manuscript): son CORNELIUS COVENHOVEN (co-executor; inherits SW half of 280-acre plantation including ~140 ac + half salt meadow; pays £225 York money to daughters/granddaughters; £150 bond he owed testator was forgiven; receives Jack immediately at testator's death — cp_ens_024 candidate). Son NICHOLAS COVENHOVEN (co-executor; inherits NE half of 280-acre plantation including ~140 ac + woodland + half salt meadow; pays £225 York money to daughters/granddaughters; receives Frank ONLY after widow's death; obligated to support widow during widowhood — STRONG HYPOTHESIS = cp_ens_022, the 1811 Somerset testator whose inventory contains Frank, Jack, and Bett). Daughter CATHARINE COVENHOVEN (£75 from Cornelius + £75 from Nicholas = £150 York money in two installments at 2 + 4 yrs from testator's decease + share of widow's wearing apparel at widow's death). Daughter ELIZABETH COVENHOVEN (£75 from Cornelius + £75 from Nicholas = £150 York money in two installments at 3 + 5 yrs from testator's decease + share of widow's wearing apparel at widow's death). Deceased son PETER COVENHOVEN (predeceased; survived by daughters). Granddaughter CATHARINE COVENHOVEN (Peter's daughter; share of £75+£75=£150 York money at 6+7 yrs from testator's decease, payable when she comes of age). Granddaughter ELIZABETH COVENHOVEN (Peter's daughter; share of £150 York money at same schedule as sister). Total bequest to daughters + granddaughters = £450 York money paid in installments over 7 yrs. | FamilySearch IDs (added 2026-04-25 Stage C — kin-anchor): son Cornelius Covenhoven (1768-1822, FS L9CF-Z4B = cp_ens_024 minted this pass); son Nicholas Covenhoven (~1772-12-31 to 1807-03-08, FS K4BM-64K, primary FaG #19078165 gravestone aged 34y 2m 8d = cp_ens_022 STRONG HYPOTHESIS — note: revised death year from prior '1811' inference); deceased son Peter (1766-1802, FS KHLF-8BN); daughter Catharine (1759-1827, FS 2CB5-6PS); daughter Elizabeth (1761-1855, FS K8BP-RZB); widow Catryna Suydam (1738-1815, FS K693-M5Z) ← the previously-unnamed widow of the 1802 will; outlived testator by 12 years.",
      "is_enslaver": true,
      "evidence_status": "documented",
      "enslaver_link": "cp_ens_023",
      "sources": "cp_sou_031 — PRIMARY: 1802-10-19 will of Nicholas Covenhoven of Franklin Twsp Somerset Co NJ; 1803-05-30 inventory; 1803-06-22 probate. Manuscript pages: /Source Documents/Nicholas Covenhoven 1802 Will/Nicholas Covenhoven 1802 Will 1.jpg + 2.jpg (will book p.339-340, recorded copy in NJ Surrogate's Office register; transcribed by Claude 2026-04-25 from Chris's high-resolution scans; \"Bett\" reading confirmed by Chris). SECONDARY: NJ Published Archives Series Vol. XXXIX (Abstract of Wills 1801-1805), Lib. 40 p.339, File 1219 R (printed editorial abstract; Ancestry.com display screenshot 2026-04-24). ANALYSIS: /Source Documents/Nicholas Covenhoven 1802 Will/Nicholas Covenhoven 1802 Will - analysis.md (renamed 2026-04-25 from \"Nicholas Covehoven 1802 Will - analysis.md\" for spelling consistency).\n\nCocheu 82:4 #661 (cp_sou_057) - primary identification of father chain + spouse Catharine Suydam + bur. Garretsen Farm. Cornelius Suydam 1768 will NJA:34:513 - confirms Catharine as his daughter. Joost Debevoise 1765 will WNYHS:8:100-01 - confirms mother Elizabeth Debevoise.",
      "notes": "KEY LEGAL MECHANISMS in this will: (1) \"in lieu of her dower\" — widow's package replaces (rather than supplements) her common-law dower right; standard elective-against-dower formula. (2) DEFERRED ENSLAVED-PERSON TRANSFER — Frank's title to son Nicholas does NOT vest until widow's death; Jack goes to Cornelius immediately. This is a structural pattern related to but distinct from the \"issue thereof\" exception in cp_ens_020's 1802 will (see feedback_issue_thereof_exception.md). The widow keeps Izabel & Bett during widowhood; Frank stays attached to the estate (likely working the inherited plantation alongside the widow's household) until her death triggers his transfer. (3) WIDOW'S FURNITURE REVERSION — \"What of her bed of what I give her during her widowhood, shall be equally divided between my two sons Cornelius & Nicholas, except her wearing apparel\" — the feather bed/cupboard/etc. reverts to sons in equal shares at widow's death; clothing goes to daughters. (4) £150 BOND FORGIVEN — son Cornelius owed the testator £150; the will \"gives\" Cornelius the bond, i.e., extinguishes the debt. (5) £450 TOTAL TO DAUGHTERS+GRANDDAUGHTERS via parallel £225 streams from each son, paid in 2-7 yr installments after testator's decease. WHY THIS WILL MATTERS for the project: this is the most explicit document yet of the gendered transfer pattern (women stay with widow for domestic labor, men go to heirs for field work) AND the deferred-title device for delaying enslaved-person transfer to align with widow's life-estate. The Frank-deferred clause is the load-bearing finding — it ties directly to the Frank/Jack/Bet trajectory hypothesis (project_franjackbet_trajectory.md) by establishing that Frank's appearance in son Nicholas's (cp_ens_022) 1811 inventory implies the widow died between 1803 and 1811. CROSS-EVENT MATCH HYPOTHESIS UPGRADE: the kinship between cp_ens_022 (1811 Nicholas) and cp_ens_023 (this row, 1802 testator) is now PRIMARY-supported by this will text (testator's son Nicholas is named as second executor + heir to NE plantation half + Frank's deferred-transfer recipient), upgrading the Parent|cp_ens_022 relationship from HYPOTHESIS to STRONG HYPOTHESIS pending only birth/death record verification of son Nicholas as the same person who died 1811 in Somerset.\n\n[2026-05-10 STAGE 82:4-T2.2] **Father chain locked**. Cocheu 82:4 #661 establishes father = Peter of Raritan = cp_fam_034 (with corrected spouse Elizabeth Debevoise per same-session Tier 1.2 fix). Full chain: Wolphert > Gerrit > Jan (cp_fam_008) > Nicasius Janse (cp_fam_027) > Peter (cp_fam_034) > **Nicholas (cp_ens_023, this row)** > Nicholas Jr. (cp_ens_022). Spouse Catharine Suydam now primary-confirmed (was \"unnamed widow\" prior). Generation/branch/sub_branch installed.",
      "raw_related_family": "",
      "raw_related_enslavers": "Father|cp_fam_034 (Peter of Raritan, Cocheu #216); Mother|Elizabeth Debevoise; Grandfather|cp_fam_027 Nicasius Janse Van Couwenhoven; Spouse|cp_fam_357; Sibling|Joseph Covenhoven of Bound Brook NJ (Cocheu #662, m. Mary Field) + Mary + Elizabeth (per father's 1786 will); Child|cp_ens_022 Nicholas Covenhoven Jr. (b.1772 d.1807); other Children: Catharine Jobs, Elizabeth, Peter, Cornelius (per cp_ens_023's own 1802 will).",
