      "notable_records": "1803-11-21 Will / proved 1804-01-21 (NJA:39:102) — Harmen Covenhoven of West Windsor, Middlesex Co. NJ; mentioned wife Phoebe, son Jacob, daughter Sarah, \"and other children\" [unnamed]. Executors: son William Covenhoven (= cp_ens_054) + son-in-law Cornelius Covenhoven (Elizabeth #541(c)'s husband). Witnesses: John Schenck, Josiah Dey, Catharine Lott. Bur. Penn's Neck Cemetery (cp_pla_074). **Will text not yet pulled — direct enslaved-person bequests pending NJA:39:102 verification (Stage 4 priority).**",
      "enslaved_people_linked": "WILL ABSTRACT REVIEWED 2026-05-29 (Ancestry NJ Abstract of Wills 1670-1817, Vol XXXIX p.102): no enslaved persons named in any bequest. INVENTORY $59.95 (File 10012 L) is DECISIVE — too small to physically contain enslaved persons (a single enslaved person at that period was typically valued $100-$300; $59.95 captures only personal effects: sorrel colt + feather bed + household goods). INHERITANCE CHAIN CHECK: son cp_ens_054 William of West Windsor was already enslaving Harry (cp_per_129) per 1801-04-04 runaway ad — 2 YEARS BEFORE Harmen's death. cp_ens_054's later 1814 Phebe + Eliza HC case (cp_eve_148) involves persons in cp_ens_054's separately-acquired household, not inherited from Harmen. STILL PENDING (low priority given inventory): (a) full will text from original Liber 40 p.430 — abstract may omit clauses (very unlikely given $59.95 inventory); (b) the design decision per session-log 2026-05-29 on demote-without-PID-rename workflow before any reclassification.",
      "will_probate": "Will dated 1803-11-21 / proved 1804-01-21 — NJA Vol XXXIX (Calendar of Wills 1801-1805) p.102; original Liber 40 p.430 (Middlesex Co.). Will-text abstract reviewed via Ancestry NJ Abstract of Wills 2026-05-29; bequests: wife Phebe use of real and personal estate during widowhood; son Jacob a sorrel colt; daughter Sarah feather bed and bedding; after wife's decease/marriage, real + personal estate to be sold and proceeds divided among 'children [unnamed], sons and daughters, share and share alike'; if any child die under age, share divided among surviving children. Executors: son William Covenhoven (= cp_ens_054) + son-in-law Cornelius Covenhoven. Witnesses: John Schenck, Josiah Dye, Catherine Loats [Lott]. 1804-01-20 Inventory $59.95 by John R. Schenck + Josiah Dye, File 10012 L.",
