      "father_text": "William Albertse Couwenhoven (cp_ens_011, b. 1702-03-09 d. 1790-03-19; will 1786-11-18 / proved 1790-03-17 NJA:36:55-56 names son William #449 along with siblings Benjamin, Joseph, Isaac, William; daughters Hendricka, Elinor, Elizabeth; grandchildren of deceased sons Albert + David and daughter Maria) — PRIMARY MATCH per Cocheu 82:1 #449 (cp_sou_054).",
      "mother_text": "Lysbeth (Elizabeth) Benjamins van Cleef (b. 1705-05-13; daughter of Benjamin & Hendrickje Sutphen Van Cleef per Van Cleef Gen. 1909 p.2; m. cp_ens_011 ~1720-1721; named \"Elizabeth wife of William Conover\" in her father Benjamin's 1747 will NJA:30:494).",
      "spouse_text": "Elizabeth Story (b. 1746, d. 1807-05-13 age 61y per Cocheu 82:1 #449 [cp_sou_054]; daughter of Thomas & Margaret Story; FS L6MR-N3L). Both bur. Cranbury Cemetery (cp_pla_075). Buried adjacent stones at Brainerd Cemetery, Cranbury.",
      "children_summary": "9 children (per Cocheu 82:1 #449 [cp_sou_054], will dated 1801-09-14 NJA:39:101-02 names sons Luke, David, Elias, Johnson, William + daughters Elizabeth Wyckoff, Margaret Schenck, Anne Bergen, Mary): (a) Anne⁷ b. 1770, m. John P. Bergen; (b) Elizabeth⁷ m. John Wyckoff; (c) Margaret⁷ d. 1804-07-18, m. Joseph Schenck; (d) **William⁷ b. 1784-08-04 d. 1837-01-21 (= cp_ens_052)**, m. Catharine Mount; (e) Luke⁷ d. 1810, m. Ann Anderson(?); (f) David⁷ b. —; (g) **Johnson⁷ b. 1781 d. 1849 (= cp_ens_049)**, m. Ann Disbrow; (h) Elias⁷ b. 1780-1845 m. Rebecca Mount(?) — cp_ens candidate per cp_ens_049 sibling-list (FS LD1Y-MBC, distinct from cp_ens_044/045/046/047 quad); (i) Mary⁷ m. Levi Updike.",
      "is_enslaver": true,
      "evidence_status": "inheritance-chain",
      "enslaver_link": "cp_ens_059",
      "sources": "Cocheu, Lincoln C. \"The Van Kouwenhoven-Conover Family.\" NYG&BR vol. LXXXII, no. 1 (January 1951): #449 (cp_sou_054). Probate: 1801-09-14 Will (NJA:39:101-02). EDSM:Ap.ix (b. 1742-03-02). FS G7FD-FG8.",
      "notes": "MINTED 2026-05-10 STAGE 82:1.B per Chris approval. Confidence flag HYPOTHESIS pending NJA:39:101-02 will text pull (Stage 4) for direct enslaved-person bequests; identification of person is MATCH-grade (Cocheu 82:1 #449 [cp_sou_054] supplies all vitals primary-source). ENSLAVER status inferred from (a) substantial estate / South Brunswick yeoman context, (b) 5/6 session memo \"4 enslaved already linked\" reference, (c) two of his sons (cp_ens_049 Johnson + cp_ens_052 William W. Jr.) held enslaved persons in next generation. **Establishes father chain for cp_ens_049 + cp_ens_052**: Wolphert > Gerrit > Willem (cp_fam_007) > Albert (cp_ens_002) > William Albertse (cp_ens_011) > **William of South Brunswick (cp_ens_059)** > [Johnson cp_ens_049 | William W. Jr. cp_ens_052]. Resolves the 5/6-memo HELD candidate. PID 059 chosen as next available after cp_ens_058 Hermanus minted earlier this session (preserving cp_ens_056/057 reservations for Peter Covenhoven of Middletown / Garret I. Conover).\n\n[2026-05-29 ANCESTRY ABSTRACT PULL] NJA:39:101-102 retrieved via Ancestry. Will silent on enslaved persons; $3,944.98 inventory total without itemization. Inheritance chain to sons cp_ens_049 + cp_ens_052 is strong (joint plantation inheritance + 11 enslaved persons documented in sons' records 1807-1822). Abstract-silence is meaningful (contemporary cp_ens_003 1793 abstract names 'negro woman Jane' — abstractors do surface enslaved persons when present) but not conclusive given large unitemized inventory total. Liber 40 p.379 / File 9960 L flagged for any future full-text confirmation. Per session-log 2026-05-29, reclassification deferred until demote-without-PID-rename design decision lands. When that decision is made, this row should likely move into a NEW evidence_status category 'inheritance-chain' or similar (proposed in Option A of session-log) — substantively distinct from cp_ens_058 'ruled-out' and cp_ens_061 'hypothesis'.",
      "raw_related_family": "",
      "raw_related_enslavers": "Father|cp_ens_011 William Albertse Couwenhoven; Mother|Lysbeth Van Cleef; Grandfather|cp_ens_002 Albert Willemse Couwenhoven; Children: cp_ens_049 Johnson + cp_ens_052 William W. Jr. + Elias 1780-1845 (FS LD1Y-MBC, cp_ens candidate not yet minted); Possible kin: cp_ens_035 Lucas Conover (POSSIBLE MATCH for son Lucas Covenhoven 1785-1810, FS L6T5-4J4 — verification pending).",
      "notable_records": "Will dated 1801-09-14 / proved 1803-03-21 (NJA:39:101-02): William Covenhoven of South Brunswick, Middlesex Co. NJ; mentioned wife Elizabeth; daughters Elizabeth Wyckoff, Margaret Schenck, Anne Bergen, Mary Covenhoven; sons Luke, David, Elias, Johnson, William. Witnesses: David Chambers, William Jordan, Cornelius Hulick. Will text NOT YET PULLED — direct enslaved-person bequests pending NJA:39:101-02 verification (Stage 4 priority). Note: 5/6 session memo records \"4 enslaved already linked\" to William W. Sr. — those linkages need cross-sheet audit (no cp_ens_HELD placeholder rows found 2026-05-10).",
      "enslaved_people_linked": "WILL ABSTRACT REVIEWED 2026-05-29 (Ancestry NJ Abstract of Wills 1670-1817, Vol XXXIX p.101-102): no enslaved persons named in any bequest. INVENTORY total $3,944.98 (File 9960 L) — large enough to potentially contain enslaved persons (comparable to cp_ens_030's $4,232.94 1815 inventory which DID name 2 enslaved persons), but abstract shows only the total without itemization. Abstract reliability check: contemporary 1793 abstract for cp_ens_003 Cornelius A. Covenhoven (same Volume series) EXPLICITLY names 'negro woman named Jane' in bequests — confirms Ancestry abstractors DO surface enslaved-person mentions when present in source. The silence here is therefore meaningful but not conclusive (inventory itemization could still surface persons abstract missed). INHERITANCE CHAIN: sons Johnson (cp_ens_049, 7 enslaved persons 1811-1822) + William Jr. (cp_ens_052, 4 enslaved persons 1814) JOINTLY INHERITED the Cranbury Neck plantation in 1803. Enslaved mothers in their post-1803 records (Kate, Betty, Nancy, Hannah) were plausibly children/teens in cp_ens_059's household at his 1803 death — but plausibility is not documentation. STILL PENDING: (a) Full probate inventory itemization from File 9960 L (Middlesex Co. Surrogate's records / NJ State Archives) — would settle the question; (b) NJ Tax Ratables for South Brunswick Twp ~1790s-1800 if surviving — slave column; (c) Design decision on demote-without-PID-rename workflow per session-log 2026-05-29. NOTE: NJ federal census schedules for 1800/1810/1820 are LOST (per session-log) — that path is not available.",
      "will_probate": "Will dated 1801-09-14 / proved 1803-03-21 — NJA Vol XXXIX (Calendar of Wills 1801-1805) p.101-102; original Liber 40 p.379 (Middlesex Co.). Will-text abstract reviewed via Ancestry NJ Abstract of Wills 2026-05-29; bequests: wife Elizabeth bed/bedding + £28 yearly in lieu of dower; daughters Elizabeth Wicoff/Wyckoff £100, Marget Schenck £100, Anne Bergen £100, Mary £100; son Lukes £375 (including obligations); son David £100 (including note); son Elias house+lot in Cranbury (bought of Benjamin Armstrong); sons Johnson (= cp_ens_049) + William (= cp_ens_052) JOINT inheritance of 'part of plantation south of the road across from Cranbury Neck' + 40 acres woodland adjoining Daniel Duncan, paying £8 yearly during mother's life; rest divided among 9 surviving children. Executors: son Lukes + sons-in-law John Wicoff + Joseph Schenck + John P. Bergin. Witnesses: David Chambers, William Jordon, Cornelius Hulick. 1803-05-18 Inventory $3,944.98 by David Chambers + Samuel Karr [Kerr], File 9960 L.",
