      "children_summary": "7 children mentioned in 1777 will + bap. records, all under age at father's death:\n(a) Margaret b. 1765-10-01, m. ca. 1785 (as 2nd wife) John A. Schenck (b. 1763-11-20, son of Albert Schenck No.236 + 2nd wife Angenetje Van Brunt);\n(b) William7 b. 1767-12-02, d. 1838-09-24, m. Mary Grover;\n(c) Roeloff b. ?, m. Elizabeth Johnson;\n(d) Jane bap. 1772-02-23 Old Tennent Church, prob. d.y.;\n(e) Elsie bap. 1774-04-24 Old Tennent Church, prob. d.y.;\n(f) Deborah b. ?, m. Zebulon Stout of Hopewell, N.J.;\n(g) Mary b. ?.",
      "is_enslaver": false,
      "evidence_status": "not-documented",
      "enslaver_link": "cp_ens_060",
      "sources": "PRIMARY: Cocheu NYG&BR 82:4 (Oct 1951) [cp_sou_057] #574 — NYG&BR vol. LXXXII no. 4 (Oct 1951) pp.211-225 — full genealogical detail. 1777 will + 1778 probate at NJA:34:291 (New Jersey Archives, Abstracts of Wills, Vol XXXIV). 1764 marriage license at NYM:218. Burial Penn's Neck Cem (cp_pla_074) per Cocheu 82:4. PENDING: NJA:34:291 direct will-text pull for enslavement evidence + WikiTree/FS PID lookup.",
      "notes": "Cocheu NYG&BR 82:4 (Oct 1951) #574 [cp_sou_057] = primary identification + lineage.\n\n## Position in family\n4th child (iv.) of #183 William5 Covenhoven (cp_fam_141) + Margaret Schenck (cp_fam_188). Sibling order per Cocheu 82:4: #571 Ann (1736), #572 Nelly (~1738), #573 Sarah (~1740), **#574 William (1742) = THIS ROW**, #575 Garret (1744 = cp_ens_061), #576 David.\n\n## Will details (1777-10-07)\nExecutors: Garret Schenck + John (son of Roeloff) Schenck, both of Penn's Neck. Witnesses: Samuel Olden, Thomas Skelton, Joseph Skelton. Wife Deborah to have use of plantation until son William turns 21. Three daughters Margaret + Deborah + Mary all under age at execution.\n\n## Geographic timeline\nBorn ~1742 Windsor Twp Middlesex Co NJ (father had migrated by 1735 from Flatlands LI) → Penn's Neck plantation by adulthood → d. 1777 Penn's Neck.\n\n## Naming pattern signals\nContinues the Wolphert > Gerrit > Willem patrilineal core — 5th 'William' in the line (after Willem Gerritsz #21, Willem Willemse #25, William of NJ #183, this #574). Eldest son William7 (b. 1767) continues to 6th.\n\n## Kin network\nFather d. 1747 when #574 was age 5. Mother Margaret Schenck remarried 1749 Derick Longstreet of Princeton. Stepfather Longstreet connection + Schenck-cousin marriages (Margaret's brothers #42 = #233 Gerrit + #235 Jan + #236 Albert) tie this row deeply into the Pleasant Valley / Marlboro / Princeton NJ Schenck-Covenhoven cluster.\n\n## Confidence note (2026-05-10)\nENSLAVER-grade mint = HYPOTHESIS pending direct NJA:34:291 will-text transcription. Genealogical facts (birth/death/marriage/parents/children) are MATCH-grade per Cocheu primary citation. Enslavement evidence is inferred from yeoman + plantation status; awaiting Stage 4 will-text pull to upgrade enslaved_people_linked + confidence_flag → MATCH. || Cocheu citation (moved from full_name 2026-05-13): Cocheu #574\n\n[2026-05-29 ANCESTRY ABSTRACT PULL] Vol XXXIV p.292 retrieved via Ancestry NJ Abstract of Wills 1670-1817 collection. Spelling note: testator surname spelled \"Kouwenhoven\" in will heading, \"Covenhoven\" for sons in same paragraph — documented spelling variation in primary source. Cocheu's page citation off by one (cited p.291; actual p.292) — corrected. Liber 20 p.196 added as the original-instrument reference for future full-text pull. Will bequests reviewed: 5 children + wife named; NO enslaved persons mentioned. Probate inventory total £571.5.0 cited without itemization — full inventory document still pending. Pending decisions until full text + full inventory pull: (a) keep on ENSLAVER sheet as identity-MATCH-only HYPOTHESIS, or (b) demote to cp_fam_NNN per [[feedback-enslaver-attribution-requires-primary-documentation]] 5/28 hard rule. See Follow-up file Project Data Sets/Follow-ups/cp_ens_060_pending_full_text_pulls_2026-05-29.md (queued).",
      "raw_related_family": "",
      "raw_related_enslavers": "Father cp_fam_141 (NOT enslaver — d. 1747); brother cp_ens_061 #575 Garret of Bethlehem Twp Hunterdon (twin-mint companion); paternal uncle cp_ens_027 Gerret Willemse Kouwenhoven of Flatlands (b.1726); cousin via Schenck-line cp_ens_058 Hermanus of Penn's Neck (Gen-6, but via different Penn's Neck William cp_fam_058).;Child|cp_ens_068",
      "notable_records": "1764-09-08 marriage license NYM:218; 1777-10-07 will (proved 1778-05-30) NJA:34:291; burial Penn's Neck Cem (cp_pla_074) per Cocheu 82:4.",
      "enslaved_people_linked": "WILL ABSTRACT REVIEWED 2026-05-29 (Ancestry NJ Abstract of Wills 1670-1817, Vol XXXIV p.292): will bequests do NOT mention enslaved persons by name or category. Bequests summarized: wife Deborah moveables; sons William + Ruliff real estate; daughters £200 cash; no slave-bequest clause. STILL PENDING: (a) full will text from original Liber 20 p.196 (abstract may omit clauses or general \"negroes\" language); (b) FULL probate inventory itemization (abstract shows only total £571.5.0 with no breakdown — compare to cp_ens_010 Roelof 1746 inventory abstract NJA:30:LibD-p420 which DID itemize \"two negro girls\" suggesting enslaved persons normally surface in abstract if present in source inventory). £571 total is small for an alleged plantation-scale enslaving yeoman; for comparison cp_ens_010's £439 included 2 enslaved persons, cp_ens_030's 1815 inventory ran $4,232 with 2 enslaved persons named. Inference: cp_ens_060 likely did NOT enslave persons documented in his estate, BUT classification decision deferred pending (a) + (b) full-text pulls.",
      "will_probate": "1777-10-07 (executed) / 1778-05-30 (proved) — NJA Vol XXXIV (Calendar of Wills 1771-1780) p.292; original Liber 20 p.196 (Middlesex Co.). Will-text abstract reviewed via Ancestry NJ Abstract of Wills 2026-05-29; bequests: wife Deborah all moveable estate; sons William + Ruliff Covenhoven the mansion house + plantation + all real estate (they to pay £200 to 3 sisters Margret, Deborah, Mary); wife to have use of plantation until son William turns 21. Executors: Garret Schenck + John Schenck (son of Ruliff), both of Penn's Neck. Witnesses: Samuel Oldden, Thomas + Joseph Skelton. 1778-05-29 Inventory £571.5.0 made by John Schenck Jr. + Thomas Skelton. [Cocheu NYG&BR 82:4 #574 — Cocheu cited \"NJA:34:291\" but actual page is 292; off-by-one corrected 2026-05-29].",
