      "mother_text": "Aeltie van Couwenhoven (cp_fam_097; 1705-1797; FS L69X-R68) — Couwenhoven by maternal line; Neeltje is doubly connected to the family (birth + marriage)",
      "spouse_text": "3 marriages: (1) Michael Field (1723-1792; FS K2TY-Q1R), m. 1763 Monmouth NJ; (2) John Elias Covenhoven (cp_ens_020; 1734-1803), m. ~1794 NJ — widowed 1803-04-21 Freehold; (3) John Bray (1743-?; FS GJ7B-2WH), m. ~1820 NJ — name at death: Elenor Bray.",
      "children_summary": "HYPOTHESIS — per the 1802 will, second-marriage children likely include \"son Peter Covenhoven\" (heir to all lands; ~7-8 in 1802 if Neeltje's son), \"eldest dau. Nelly,\" and grandson John Covenhoven. FS GJ7Y-PV2's second-marriage children block was cut off in the screenshot Chris shared and remains unread. Open: whether \"Peter\" was Neeltje's son via John (Neeltje would be ~50-52 at his birth, biologically tight) or a step-grandchild via John's son Elias.",
      "is_enslaver": true,
      "evidence_status": "documented",
      "enslaver_link": "cp_ens_021",
      "sources": "PRIMARY: 1802-12-14 will of John Covenhoven (widow-beneficiary clause) + 1803 probate inventory sub-block \"to the widow by will,\" FamilySearch DGS 007637520 frames 00719-00729 (= Monmouth Probate File 5980 M); local copies at /Source Documents/John Covenhoven of Monmouth 1803 Will and Probate/. 1812-06-03 manumission of Ceazer + 1822-08-26 manumission of Rachel, NJ Monmouth County manumission records (Active rows cp_per_057 + cp_per_061). AGGREGATOR (HYPOTHESIS-grade): FamilySearch KPHS-YKZ (linked from John Covenhoven GJ7Y-PV2 spouse field; not yet directly inspected). CROSS-REFERENCE: John Covenhoven cp_ens_020.",
      "notes": "Neeltje is identifiable as the \"Eleanor Covenhoven\" of John's 1802 will by Dutch-English first-name equivalence — \"Neeltje\" = \"Nelly\" = \"Eleanor\" — plus chronological fit (John's first wife Eleanor Williams Wyckoff died 1793, before the will). Per FS KPHS-YKZ she is John's second wife, married ~1794. The 1802 will's clause \"all the negroes that came by her excepting the issue thereof\" is the load-bearing legal mechanism: Neeltje inherits the dowry-enslaved adults she brought into the marriage but their children stay in the main estate to be distributed among John's heirs from his first marriage. The 1803 inventory's two-block structure ('main' + 'to the widow by will') makes the partition explicit on the page. The \"to the widow by will\" sub-block names exactly three people — Cezar, Suki, Rose — strongly suggesting these are the three dowry-enslaved adults Neeltje brought to her ~1794 marriage and held as separate property under the will. CEZAR LIFE TRAJECTORY (MATCH this commit): cp_per_113 Cezar (1803 inherited) and cp_per_057 Ceazer (1812 manumitted by widow Eleanor) are the same person — same name, same household, same widow, 9-year window consistent with one life. This is the project's first fully traced cross-event life trajectory across two enslaver households (Col. John Covenhoven → widow Neeltje), per project_cezar_life_trajectory.md. FamilySearch ID: KPHS-YKZ (linked from John Covenhoven GJ7Y-PV2 spouse field; not yet directly inspected). Five siblings per FS (verified 2026-05-25): Antje 1730-1757 (KN42-TD1), Patience 1733-1819 (29SL-YMT — \"Sister Patience\" of 1817 will), Helena 1735-1772 (L4B5-B79), Aert 1739-1742 (LCXC-8X3, brother d. toddler), Jannetje 1741-? (9KFM-JV8). Only Patience survived to 1817; her son Garret Wyckoff is co-executor.",
      "raw_related_family": "",
      "raw_related_enslavers": "Spouse|cp_ens_020",
      "notable_records": "(a) Beneficiary of John Covenhoven's 1802-12-14 will — receives \"all the negroes that came by her excepting the issue thereof\"; (b) Inventoried as widow-recipient of cp_per_113 (Cezar), cp_per_114 (Suki), and cp_per_090 (Rose) in the 1803 probate sub-block \"to the widow by will\" (FamilySearch DGS 007637520 frame 00727); (c) 1812-06-03 manumission of Ceazer (cp_per_113, formerly cp_per_057) — manumitter recorded as \"Eleanor Covenhoven\", cp_eve_026; (d) 1815-02-25 + 1816-08-28 BBB registrations of James Henry (cp_per_209, cp_eve_041) and Ephraim (cp_per_210, cp_eve_065) sons of Rachel (cp_per_208), filed as \"Eleanor Conover of the Village & Township of Freehold\"; (e) 1822-08-26 manumission of Rachel age ~24 (cp_per_208, cp_eve_071, Monmouth Manumission Book pp. 88-89, full statutory wrapper; recorded 1822-09-06; consolidated 2026-05-05 with the BBB mother row). (f) Own 1817 Will (cp_sou_084) — testamentary manumission clause for 5 enslaved persons (Phillis, Jacob, James, Leah, Rachel); probated 1830-06-05 by John Bray (3rd husband, co-executor) + Garret Wyckoff (nephew, son of sister Patience Williamson Wyckoff).",
      "enslaved_people_linked": "cp_per_113 (Cezar — inherited 1803 via \"came-by-her\" provision; manumitted 1812 cp_eve_026; former cp_per_057 retired Freed PIDs row 12) | cp_per_114 (Suki — inherited 1803 via \"came-by-her\") | cp_per_090 (Rose — inherited 1803 via \"came-by-her\") | cp_per_208 (Rachel — BBB mother of James Henry cp_per_209 + Ephraim cp_per_210; manumitted 1822-08-26 cp_eve_071; consolidated 2026-05-05 from former cp_per_061 into cp_per_208) | cp_per_209 (James Henry — son of Rachel, b. 1815 cp_eve_041) | cp_per_210 (Ephraim — son of Rachel, b. 1816 cp_eve_065).",
      "will_probate": "(pending — Neeltje died 1830 in NJ; investigation of Monmouth County 1830-1832 probate index would resolve. If she left a will, it would document post-1822 disposition of remaining enslaved people in her household.)",
