      "enslaver_link": "cp_ens_001",
      "sources": "WikiTree Covenhoven-21 https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Covenhoven-21 ; Find a Grave Memorial 66234789 (Nicholas Cowenhoven Esq.) https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/66234789/nicholas-cowenhoven ; Center for Brooklyn History — Cowenhoven receipt books (1782-1787), NYU finding aid bcms_0095 https://findingaids.library.nyu.edu/cbh/bcms_0095/ ; 'All Roots Lead to Brooklyn: The Last Homestead of Modern Bensonhurst' (Brooklyn Genealogy blog, 2015) http://brooklyngenealogy.blogspot.com/2015/10/the-last-homestead-of-modern-bensonhurst.html Find a Grave Memorial #66234789 (https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/66234789/nicholas-cowenhoven) — gravestone photograph by Christopher Barnes (Chris) — gravestone photo received 2026-04-25 from Chris.",
      "notes": "Identified as the enslaver in 7 Active rows by exact-string match on 'Nicholas Covenhoven', with AKA='Judge' explicitly affixed on 3 of those rows. Three rows pass the Rule 3 three-prong test (name + dates + place all align with documented historical person) and are committed as MATCH: cp_per_041 (Jack, sold 1782 in New Utrecht), cp_per_042 (Cuffee, sold 1785 in New Utrecht), cp_per_043 (Bet, sold 1792 in New Utrecht — within 1 year of Judge Nicholas's March 1793 death). Four additional Active rows currently strung as 'Nicholas Covenhoven' fail the three-prong test and are deliberately LEFT UNPROCESSED (no enslaverID written) pending Chris's source research: cp_per_044 and cp_per_045 (Thomas, Neen — manumitted-in-will events 1810 in Brooklyn; date is 17 years after Judge Nicholas's death and location is Brooklyn rather than New Utrecht, so candidate enslavers include Judge Nicholas's son John Nicholas Cowenhoven or a different Nicholas Cowenhoven entirely); cp_per_138 and cp_per_139 (Margaret, Charles — May 1784 legal proceeding in 'State of New Jersey'; within his lifespan but Judge Nicholas presided over a New York court, so a NJ proceeding requires document-level explanation). Other Active strings starting with 'Nicholas' represent distinct persons and are NOT linked to cp_ens_001: 'Nicholas R. Covenhoven' (5 rows, 1810-01-27 Brooklyn — middle-initial difference + post-death dates), 'Nicholas Cowehoven [Covenhoven]' (4 rows, 1803-06-22 Franklin Township Somerset NJ — post-death + different jurisdiction). **GRAVESTONE PRIMARY (added 2026-04-25):** Inscription reads: 'In memory of NICHOLAS COWENHOVEN Esquire, who departed this life the 7th of March 1793, aged 48 years and 6 months.' (per Chris's photo and reading 2026-04-25). Find a Grave Memorial #66234789 (https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/66234789/nicholas-cowenhoven) — gravestone photograph by Christopher Barnes (Chris). Inscription supplies primary death date (1793-03-07 ✓) and primary-by-inference birth date (circa September 1744; precision month-only). **WIKITREE-CONFLICT RESOLUTION:** WikiTree-derived 1744-04-18 birth date conflicts with the gravestone-derived ~September 1744 by ~5 months. Per `feedback_genealogy_aggregator_authority`, gravestone wins; WikiTree date moved to discovery-pointer status only. Confirmed 2026-04-25 by Chris.\n\n**Children George + John identified 2026-04-25 (Chris):** see cp_ens_018 + cp_ens_019 rows for primary documentation (1790 federal census Town of New Utrecht, where Judge Nicholas + son George are the first two heads of household in the township). 1790 household held 10 enslaved people (significantly more than the 3 named in current Active linkages cp_per_041/042/043 from the 1782/1785/1792 sales) — Stage C-4 will mint a cp_rec_### UNNAMED row for the 1790 group + scan for any additional named-individual records for him in the 1782-1793 window. | 2026-05-17 ENRICHMENT (cp_famsou_022 1792 Clinton endorsement): Clintonian / Anti-Federalist political alignment attested — endorsed George Clinton for re-election as NY Governor in the famously contested 1792 election (vs. John Jay). Chaired Kings County Freeholders' meeting at Flatbush March 1, 1792 — confirmed active community leader role 1 year before death. Brother cp_ens_034 served on the same meeting's Committee of Correspondence; the brothers were jointly mobilizing the Brooklyn-Dutch vote for Clinton. Political contrast with nephew cp_ens_026 (Flatlands) who was indicted as Loyalist by NY State in 1783 (cp_famsou_013) — Brooklyn-Dutch Cowenhovens were politically split during/after the war.\n\n**2026-05-21 Cocheu discrepancy review cleanup (cp_ens_001 own-row pass):** Wired to Cocheu #654 (1989 reprint p.84, NYG&BR 82:4 Oct 1951), listed as child v. of John⁵ Covenhoven #214 (cp_ens_007). Spouse field collapsed to bare PID (was carrying parents-of-spouse + dowry context); the marriage date/place moved to dedicated cols (marriage_date 1763-09-24, marriage_place New York City). Father field collapsed to bare PID; the cp_ens_034 1778-inventory disambig prose previously in father col is preserved here for the historical record: “Brooklyn-line; per cp_ens_034's primary-confirmed identification (1778 inventory of cp_ens_007 names 3 executor sons: Rem b.1734=cp_ens_006, Judge Nicholas b.1744=cp_ens_001, John b.1752=cp_ens_034).” Spouse parents (Joris Lott + Maria Van Brunt) and dowry note (“brought hundreds of acres in New Utrecht as her dowry”) previously inline in spouse col are kept on this row for context but belong on cp_ens_015's row long-term. Place_ids backfilled: birth_place=cp_pla_009, death_place=cp_pla_009, marriage_place=cp_pla_038, burial_place=cp_pla_053. DOB discrepancy with Cocheu noted in birth_record (Cocheu #654 gives Apr. 18, 1744; gravestone-derived ∼Sept 1744 retained per 2026-04-25 primary-evidence resolution).\n\n## 2026-05-22 BACK-LINK FIX (1790 census reciprocity)\n- enslaved_people_linked appended cp_rec_011 (1790 US Federal Census, Town of New Utrecht — 10 enslaved persons in Judge Nicholas's household). Forward link (UNNAMED.enslaver_name → 'Nicholas Cowenhoven (Judge Nicholas) (cp_ens_001)') was already correctly wired; only the reciprocal was missing. Per Chris 2026-05-22.",
      "raw_related_family": "",
      "raw_related_enslavers": "Parent|cp_ens_007; Spouse|cp_ens_015; Child|cp_ens_018; Child|cp_ens_019; Sibling|cp_ens_006; Sibling|cp_ens_034; Sibling|cp_fam_326; Sibling|cp_fam_327; Mother|cp_fam_332",
      "notable_records": "Account and receipt books 1782-1787 at Center for Brooklyn History (Cowenhoven receipt books, NYU finding aid bcms_0095) — include receipts for purchases of enslaved people from neighbors and cousins. Cowenhoven-Benson mansion in Town of New Utrecht (present-day Bath Beach, Brooklyn) — known for a millstone doorstep, basement chains used to punish the enslaved, and entertaining George Washington and other luminaries. Buried at New Utrecht Reformed Church cemetery (cp_pla_053) alongside wife Jannetje (Jane) Lott.\n\n1790 FEDERAL CENSUS — Town of New Utrecht, Kings County NY (Household #3, first head of household in New Utrecht). Tally per Chris's 2026-04-25 image: free white males 16+: 4; under 16: 0; free white women: 2; all other free persons: 1; SLAVES: 10; total 17 persons. The 'all other free persons: 1' = a free Black household member (free Black labor co-resident with enslaved labor — unusual to document); the 4 free white males 16+ include Judge Nicholas himself + adult son John N. (cp_ens_019, age 21) + 2 unidentified adult males (other adult sons or extended family — primary research follow-up). Adjacent Household #3a is son George Cowenhoven (cp_ens_018) — also independently enslaving 4 people. Combined Cowenhoven New Utrecht enslaved-person count in 1790 = 14 across the two households. | cp_famsou_022 (1792-03-01 chaired Kings County Freeholders' meeting at Dr. James Van Beuren's house, Flatbush, signed as \"NICHOLAS COWENHOVEN, Chairman\" per Daily Advertiser Mar 3, 1792; unanimously endorsed Gov. George Clinton for re-election and Pierre Van Cortlandt for Lt. Gov.; meeting also appointed a 28-member Committee of Correspondence including himself and his brother cp_ens_034 to promote Clinton's candidacy). Confirms his active civic leadership 1 year + 6 days before death (1793-03-07).",
