      "children_summary": "8 children, ALL bap. in the German Reformed Church in Hunterdon County:\n(a) Sarah bap. 1767-02-12;\n(b) William7 bap. 1769-02-14, m. Jane Petty, d. 1856-04-15;\n(c) Hannah bap. 1773-03-02;\n(d) David bap. 1776-08-03 — co-administrator of father's 1810 estate;\n(e) Peggie bap. 1779-03-09;\n(f) Mercy7 bap. 1781-08-14, d. 1831-03-30, m. Cornelius Wyckoff (d. 1833-08-09, son of Peter & — (Verdervoort) Wyckoff — Wyckoff Fam. 1950 p.58);\n(g) Garret bap. 1784-06-01, m. Mary Stiger;\n(h) Mary bap. 1787-05-25.",
      "is_enslaver": false,
      "evidence_status": "not-documented",
      "enslaver_link": "cp_ens_061",
      "sources": "PRIMARY: Cocheu NYG&BR 82:4 (Oct 1951) [cp_sou_057] #575 — NYG&BR vol. LXXXII no. 4 (Oct 1951) pp.211-225 — full genealogical detail. 1810 estate inventory + probate at NJA:41:87-88 (New Jersey Archives, Abstracts of Wills, Vol XLI). Wyckoff Family 1950 p.58 cited by Cocheu for daughter Mercy + Cornelius Wyckoff. PENDING: NJA:41:87-88 direct inventory text pull for enslavement evidence + WikiTree/FS PID lookup.",
      "notes": "Cocheu NYG&BR 82:4 (Oct 1951) #575 [cp_sou_057] = primary identification + lineage.\n\n## Position in family\n5th child (v.) of #183 William5 Covenhoven (cp_fam_141) + Margaret Schenck (cp_fam_188). Sibling order per Cocheu 82:4: #571 Ann (1736), #572 Nelly (~1738), #573 Sarah (~1740), #574 William (1742 = cp_ens_060), **#575 Garret (1744) = THIS ROW**, #576 David.\n\n## Geographic timeline\nBap. 1744-09-30 Freehold-Middletown Dutch Church (Monmouth Co.) → migrated to Hunterdon County by ~1766 (marriage to Hannah White of Shrewsbury, NJ) → settled Bethlehem Township → d. 1810-07-23 Hunterdon Co., bur. Grandin (cp_pla_080).\n\n## Denominational shift\nChildren ALL bap. in **German Reformed Church** in Hunterdon County — denominational shift from Dutch Reformed (his own baptism) to German Reformed reflects the Hunterdon Co. religious landscape and intermarriage into local English/German settler population (wife Hannah White's family).\n\n## Estate (1810)\nInventory $4,673.43 — substantial planter estate. Administrators = sons William7 (b. 1769) + David (b. 1776). Appraisers Peter Van Sickle + Charles Carter — locally prominent Bethlehem Twp surnames. Inventory sworn 1810-08-28, less than 6 weeks after death — suggests organized estate planning.\n\n## Naming pattern signals\nEldest son William7 (b. 1769) continues the Willem patriline; youngest son Garret (b. 1784) carries father's name. Daughter Mercy7 (b. 1781) marries Cornelius Wyckoff — Wyckoff intermarriage echoes the broader Couwenhoven-Wyckoff cousin network in NJ.\n\n## Kin network\nBrother of cp_ens_060 #574 William of Penn's Neck — paired Gen-6 mints from same parents. Father died when Garret was age 3 (1747); mother Margaret remarried 1749 Derick Longstreet of Princeton. Migration to Hunterdon Co. via wife's Shrewsbury NJ family connection.\n\n## Confidence note (2026-05-10)\nENSLAVER-grade mint = HYPOTHESIS pending direct NJA:41:87-88 inventory text. Genealogical facts (birth/death/marriage/parents/children) are MATCH-grade per Cocheu primary citation. Enslavement evidence is inferred from planter-scale estate + Hunterdon Co. 1810 context; awaiting Stage 4 inventory text pull to upgrade enslaved_people_linked + confidence_flag → MATCH. || Cocheu citation (moved from full_name 2026-05-13): Cocheu #575",
      "raw_related_family": "",
      "raw_related_enslavers": "Brother cp_ens_060 #574 William of Penn's Neck (twin-mint companion); paternal uncle cp_ens_027 Gerret Willemse Kouwenhoven of Flatlands; via mother, Schenck-Couwenhoven cluster cousins. Son William7 (b. 1769) and son David (b. 1776) served as 1810 estate administrators per NJA:41:87.",
      "notable_records": "~1766 marriage to Hannah White; 1810-07-23 death; 1810-08-23 inventory (Peter Van Sickle + Charles Carter), sworn 1810-08-28 by sons William + David Covenhoven as administrators (NJA:41:87-88); estate $4,673.43; burial Grandin NJ (cp_pla_080).",
      "enslaved_people_linked": "(pending NJA:41:87-88 direct inventory text pull — Cocheu reports $4,673.43 estate but does not quote slave-inventory items; 1810 Hunterdon Co. planters frequently held enslaved persons during NJ gradual abolition era, but enslavement evidence here is HYPOTHESIS until NJA inventory is read; primary verification deferred to Stage 4)",
