      "spouse_text": "Catherine Stellerwerf (cp_ens_017), b. 1746, d. 1843. Marriage date pending primary; both spouses born 1746; Johannes predeceased Catherine by ~20 years. Catherine listed as 'Mrs. Conover' on 1830 New Utrecht census p394 succeeding him as primary household enslaver.",
      "children_summary": "Per Cocheu 82:4 #659 (cp_sou_057, p. 224) — TEN children across THREE marriages: BY 1st WIFE Margaret Ammerman (m. 1768-02-28, d. 1780-09-22): (a) Antje⁷ b. 1769-07-23, d. 1845-08-16, m. Jacobus Van Nuys; (b) Jannetje⁷ b. 1771-09-17, d. 1774-09-06 (d.y.); (c) Sarah⁷ b. 1774-04-22, d. 1854-04-21, m. 1792-01-14 John Hanse of New Utrecht (at Flatlands). BY 2nd WIFE Elizabeth Van Pelt (m. 1781-08-03, d. 1786-03-23): (d) Gertrude⁷ b. 1782-06-01, d. 1865-04-01, m. 1801-01-08 Roelof Van Brunt; (e) Margaret⁷ b. 1784-05-05, d. 1867-08-01, m. Coert Gerritsen of Somerville NJ; (f) Elizabeth⁷ b. 1786-03-23, d. 1871-02-15, unmar. BY 3rd WIFE Catharine Stellenwerf (= cp_ens_017, m. 1787-06-24): (g) Phebe⁷ b. 1789-03-17, d. 1868-11-01, unmar.; (h) Garret⁷ b. 1791-08-27, d. 1828-09-06, m. 1818-03-11 Catharine Bergen (b. 1791-10-29, d. 1828-10-02 — both died within a month of each other). NO enslaver attestation currently documented in the project dataset for this Garret⁷ — pending future mint as cp_fam_NNN OR cp_ens_NNN once attestation surfaces. [CORRECTION 2026-05-17: an earlier hypothesis (since RETRACTED) attributed the 1822 manumission of Nan (cp_per_003) to this Garret⁷ via the 'Garret J.' rendering on that deed and a 'J. = Johannes-son' patronymic reading. The 'Garret J.' rendering was confirmed by Chris on 2026-04-25 to be a scribal variant for cp_ens_014 (Garrett Cowenhoven b. 1774-05-02, d. 1840-01-28, son of Nicasius Cowenhoven by cp_fam_033 Gerret's branch — i.e., this Garret⁷'s first-cousin, NOT his identical twin). Garret⁷ is therefore NOT the 1822 Nan manumitter; that is cp_ens_014. See cp_eve_113 + cp_ens_014 record + cp_famsou_008 disambiguation note.] (i) Jacob⁷ b. 1795-01-11, d. 1826-07-22 = cp_fam_300 (Capt. Jacob Cowenhoven of New Utrecht; m. 1824-08-28 Anne Van Nuys; no children; see cp_famsou_005 for the Long-Island Star death notice and Cocheu cross-confirmation, per Chris 2026-05-17). (j) Nicholas⁷ b. 1796-10-30, d. 1841-05-29, m. Matilda Dingee (b. 1807-10-10, d. 1861-01-19). Pending mint. Cocheu cites 'Bergen Fam. 1876, p.329' at end of #659.",
      "is_enslaver": true,
      "evidence_status": "documented",
      "enslaver_link": "cp_ens_013",
      "sources": "WikiTree Van_Couwenhoven-85 (https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Van_Couwenhoven-85); Father Gerret's 1781 will: NY Wills and Probate Records 1659-1999, Vol 0035-0039 pp.222-225 (cf. cp_fam_033, cp_rec_007); Town of New Utrecht \"Births and Manumissions of Slaves\" + \"Records of Strays\" — Old Town Records Collection, NYC Municipal Archives (https://nycrecords.access.preservica.com/uncategorized/IO_e89e72bd-74e7-425e-8da9-1de8c2e19fea/); per Active rows for cp_per_003 (img #127), cp_per_004 (img #129), cp_per_020-023.; FAMILY_SOURCES cp_famsou_002 — 1776 Kings County Loyalty Address subscriber list (printed verbatim as 'James Cowenhoven' on p.2; identification as Johannes Van Couwenhoven of New Utrecht per Chris 2026-05-17).; Cocheu 82:4 #659 (cp_sou_057, NYG&B Record 82.4 Oct 1951, p. 224) — primary genealogical attestation of Johannes⁶'s 10 children across 3 marriages, added to children_summary 2026-05-17. Children minted/queued: cp_fam_300 (Jacob⁷ Capt. of New Utrecht; see also cp_famsou_005). Pending mints: Garret⁷ (the workbook-hypothesized 'Garret J. Cowenhoven'), Phebe⁷ unmar., Nicholas⁷, plus 6 children of the 1st and 2nd marriages.",
      "notes": "Brooklyn / New Utrecht branch (Jan-Gerretse line via Wolphert → Gerrit → Jan Gerretse → Nicasius Janse → Gerret cp_fam_033 → Johannes). Inheritor of share of \"All my Negroes\" via Gerret's 1781 will (UNNAMED cp_rec_007); the 5 New Utrecht linkages 1806–1822 plausibly include descendants of those held in 1781 — births start 25 yrs after the will. KIN CONTEXT: nephew of cp_ens_007 John (1707–1778); first cousin of cp_ens_006 Rem (1734–1783); first cousin once removed of cp_ens_005 (Bedford Nicholas) and cp_ens_008 John R. All 5 enslaved-people linkages = MATCH per name+place+date convergence (Chris confirmed 2026-04-25). FOLLOW-UPS: (a) confirm Garret J. Cowenhoven as cp_ens_014 candidate (manumitter of cp_per_003 Nan 1822-06-06); (b) fill mother/spouse/death_place from WikiTree Van_Couwenhoven-85 in next pass; (c) archive Gerret 1781 will under /Source Documents/.\n\n**Spouse resolved 2026-04-25:** Catherine Stellerwerf (cp_ens_017); see her row for 1830 census documentation of her continuing the New Utrecht enslaving role 1823–1843. PDF 2 high-res read confirms 0 enslaved + 8 free colored in Catherine's 1830 household — strong evidence of joint pre-1827 enslaving by Johannes + Catherine.",
      "raw_related_family": "",
      "raw_related_enslavers": "Parent|cp_fam_033; Spouse|cp_ens_017",
      "notable_records": "(1) 1781-05-09 will of father Gerret (cp_fam_033, NY Wills Vol 0035-0039 pp.222-225) — Johannes inherits 1/3 of \"All my Negroes\" + furniture. (2) Town of New Utrecht Births and Manumissions of Slaves: birth indentures under 1799 law for Sare 1806 (cp_per_020), Mary 1808 (cp_per_021), Cate 1810 (cp_per_022), Tom 1813 (cp_per_023); manumission of Jack age 30 on 1822-05-20 (cp_per_004, image #129). (3) cp_per_003 Nan manumission 1822-06-06 by Garret J. Cowenhoven names Johannes among \"Other people mentioned\" — corroborating his presence in New Utrecht as of 1822. (4) 1776-11-13 (publ. 1776-12-09) — subscriber on the Kings County Loyalty Address to Lord Howe and Governor William Tryon, printed in The New-York Gazette and the Weekly Mercury No. 1311 (Hugh Gaine, NY) on the address subscriber list at p.2 middle column. Name printed verbatim as 'James Cowenhoven'; identified as Johannes (= cp_ens_013) by Chris 2026-05-17 on the basis of the New Utrecht qualifier and the absence of any other adult Johannes/James/Jacobus Cowenhoven in New Utrecht in 1776. Co-signers from the immediate Cowenhoven kin network: first cousin Rem cp_ens_006 (Brooklyn), cousin-once-removed Judge Nicholas cp_ens_001 (New Utrecht), and the two Flatlands Kouwenhoven men cp_ens_026 (William) and cp_ens_027 (Gerret Willemse). The 'James'-for-'Johannes' typesetting choice in this print is unusual — Hugh Gaine's shop set four other Dutch 'Johannes' names correctly on the same p.2 column — and is flagged for future investigation. See SOURCE cp_famsou_002 for full context, verbatim transcription, and typesetting note.",
