      "notes": "MINTED 2026-05-05 PM (this session) inline per Chris approval, on a 2-record manuscript evidence chain (cp_eve_085 Frances Lane + cp_eve_086 Samuel Lane — same-day 9 Aug 1828 manumissions, same Township of Middletown, same lead witnesses William Conover + James Hopping). Per project precedent, 2-record manuscript chain is sufficient for inline cp_ens mint even without external biographical anchor (cf. cp_ens_039 John I. Covenhoven, cp_ens_040 Garret Covenhoven Upper Freehold — both minted 5/5 PM on similar 2-record chains plus optional anchors). Initial WikiTree + Find A Grave search 2026-05-05 returned no specific 'Daniel G. Conover Middletown' match — anchor pending future search. DISAMBIGUATION: distinct from R79+R80 'Daniel D. Conover' (different middle initial 'D.' vs 'G.' = almost certainly a different Conover; R79+R80 mint pending future ingestion). KIN SIGNAL: William Conover witness on both 1828 deeds — possible relative; watch for re-attestation.\n\n[2026-05-10] Vitals backfilled via Cocheu 82:2 #509 (cp_sou_055). Father chain now MATCH: Wolphert > Gerrit > Willem (cp_fam_007) > Jacob (cp_ens_009) > Gerret Jacobse (cp_fam_131) > **Daniel G. (cp_ens_042)**. Previously all vitals pending — 1828 manumission witness chain (cp_eve_085, cp_eve_086) corroborated by Cocheu primary genealogy.\n\n**ENRICHED 2026-05-10 (9 (none)-bucket attribution arc):** 6 of 7 children now formally minted as cp_fam rows (cp_fam_203 Margaret Rezeau wife + cp_fam_204-208 unmint-enslaver children + cp_ens_043 already minted enslaver son; cp_ens_041 already minted enslaver son). Burial location now formally tied to cp_pla_081 Conover Family Burial Ground (new mint this commit).",
