      "notes": "Brooklyn-line; youngest of three executor sons of cp_ens_007 (birth-order: Rem b.1734 = cp_ens_006; Judge Nicholas b.1744 = cp_ens_001; John b.1752 = cp_ens_034). Identification primary-confirmed 2026-04-28 by combination of 1778 inventory (3 executor sons match FS sibling list of cp_ens_007) + 30 June 1789 Brooklyn deed naming him 'his uncle' to nephew Nicholas R. (cp_ens_005). Important disambiguation: cp_fam_049 in FAMILY sheet is a SEPARATE John (b. before 1753, son of cp_fam_029 d. by 1753) — earlier project hypothesis that conflated this John with cp_fam_049 has been retired. cp_ens_034 IS the 1790 Brooklyn AMBIG John household (cp_rec_017). Pending: WikiTree profile creation; primary baptism + death records; locator-map check on Aughtieste Kamp parcel. | 2026-05-17 ENRICHMENT (cp_famsou_022 1792 Clinton endorsement): Committee of Correspondence member at age 40; first documented political role. Worked alongside his brother cp_ens_001 Judge Nicholas (chair). Clintonian / Anti-Federalist political alignment attested. Same Brooklyn-Dutch network as cp_famsou_010 (1780 merchant partnership with John Remsen) — confirms cp_ens_034's continued integration into the Brooklyn-Dutch civic elite through the 1790s.",
