      "raw_related_family": "",
      "raw_related_enslavers": "Parent|cp_ens_027;Sibling|cp_ens_028;Child|cp_ens_029",
      "notable_records": "1777-09-13 Will of father Garret Kouwenhoven (NYSA J0038-92 SS2 2869): named executor at age 19, alongside elder brother Peter, plus non-family executors Nicholas Schanck (Schenck) and John Ranson; co-inherited home farm \"on the South Side\" with brother Peter, equal division. 1778-01-15 Sworn in as executor before Surrogate Cary Ludlow, City and County of New York (per will probate endorsement page 6). 1778-12-12 Marriage to Annatie Wyckoff at Flatlands. 1790 US Census, Town of Flatlands, Kings County NY (FS ark XHKP-BKX): household 1 wm≥16 / 1 wm<16 / 4 wf / 0 other free / 8 enslaved. 1800 US Census, Flatlands (FS ark XH5T-PBJ — HYPOTHESIS continuity, pending image read). 1810 US Census, Flatlands (FS ark XH2T-D9D, transcribed \"William Howenhoven\" — HYPOTHESIS continuity, pending image read). Possibly 1820 \"Wm Covenhwen\" Flatbush (FS ark XHGZ-X28) but town change introduces ambiguity. Find a Grave Memorial #240115836. Town of Flatlands birth-indenture register entries naming William Kouwenhoven as enslaver (NYC Municipal Archives, Brooklyn Old Town Records, Flatlands; SOURCE-BOTR-Flatlands-Birth_Registers_and_Manumissions_of_Enslaved_People; https://nycrecords.access.preservica.com/uncategorized/IO_c48e45ec-2ae4-43a5-99dd-71a0e3fdb085/): cp_per_025 John (b.1800-01-09), cp_per_028 Saar (b.1802-09-15, abandonment), cp_per_029 Hanna (mother of Saar), cp_per_031 Jack (b.1806-10-15), cp_per_032 John (b.1807), cp_per_033 Dick (b.1808), cp_per_034 Isabel (mother of Dick) — 7 rows total = 5 indentured children under 1799 NY Act + 2 enslaved mothers (Hanna, Isabel). | 1792-08-25 JOINT SALE of Bet (cp_per_043) to nephew Judge Nicholas Covenhoven cp_ens_001 with co-seller Johannis Remsen for £25 — receipt at Center for Brooklyn History (Nicholas Covenhoven Papers, NYU finding aid bcms_0095); cp_sou_027 / cp_eve_130. Signed 'W[m.] Kouwenhoven' (4-letter Kouw, Flatlands K-spelling). FIRST documented K-spelling Flatlands William attestation in this dataset, predating his 1800-1808 Flatlands BOTR enslaver records by 8 years. Intra-kinship transaction (William=paternal kin via Flatlands branch; Remsen=Nicholas's maternal-line kin via Catharina Remsen) suggests within-family asset reallocation rather than market acquisition.",
      "enslaved_people_linked": "**7 MATCH (Flatlands BOTR birth register, 1800-1808):** cp_per_025 John, cp_per_028 Saar, cp_per_029 Hanna (mother of Saar), cp_per_031 Jack, cp_per_032 John, cp_per_033 Dick, cp_per_034 Isabel (mother of Dick). Mapped 2026-04-26 from Active sweep — name+location+date+Town-Clerk-role all converge. 8 unnamed enslaved persons in 1790 Flatlands household — HOLD on UNNAMED minting per Chris 2026-04-26 (await census-wide pass). Possible inheritance link: any of mother Antie's 2 widowhood-tenancy enslaved women (cp_rec_010 from cp_ens_027 1777 will) could have devolved to William post-1782 if she died and the wenches reverted/redistributed — speculative pending probate evidence. | **+1 from 1792 Bet sale (added 2026-05-07):** cp_per_043 Bet (held by William cp_ens_026 up to and through 1792-08-25 joint sale to nephew Nicholas Covenhoven cp_ens_001; pre-Town-Clerk-era / pre-1800-BOTR; cp_eve_130). Total now 8 enslaved persons linked to cp_ens_026 across 1792-1808 window.",
      "will_probate": "(pending — Kings County NY Surrogate, 1825 probate index search recommended; would document children + any post-1827 enslavement holdings)",
      "burial_location": "(pending — Flatlands Reformed Church Cemetery candidate, per FaG #240115836 placement; primary cemetery confirmation needed)",
