      "sources": "Cocheu 82:2 #514 (cp_famsou_028, .md line 2879); FG Memorial 31237518 (cp_famsou_NNN — see follow-ups); 1802 Monmouth Surrogate Probate File 8480 M (cp_sou_088); FamilySearch GQW4-NXB; gravestone Old Brick Reformed Church Cemetery, Marlboro, Plot B 71",
      "notes": "MINTED 2026-05-28. Identity primary-source-locked via 5-source convergence (gravestone, 1802 LOA, Cocheu #514, FS GQW4-NXB, FG #31237518 — full enumeration in `sources` field; gravestone + LOA verbatim text on cp_sou_088.Source_Quotation). Middle initial \"G.\" = father-patronymic (\"son of Garret/Gerret\"), same convention as brother Daniel G. #509 (= cp_ens_042) and as son Elias I. (= \"son of John\"). Rev War Pvt per FG gravesite detail. Per cp_eve_025 precedent, debtors named in the inventory (Elias Conover, George Morris, Garret G. Schanck) are not separately minted as enslavers — debtor/administrator detail lives in cp_eve_173.notes.",
      "raw_related_family": "",
      "raw_related_enslavers": "Father|cp_fam_131 Gerret Jacobse Couwenhoven; Mother|cp_fam_325 Neeltje Schenck Couwenhoven; Spouse|cp_fam_098 Jane Schenck",
      "notable_records": "cp_eve_173 (1802 Probate [Inventory], Monmouth Surrogate File 8480 M, NJ Wills 8425m–8536m p. 392; intestate; LOA sworn 1802-05-29 at Freehold; $9,812 administration bond same date; administered by widow Jane + son Elias). Filed at NJ Prerogative Office at Trenton.",
      "enslaved_people_linked": "cp_per_260 Jake (\"Blackman Jake\" per inventory verbatim); cp_per_261 Sal (\"black gal Sal\" per inventory verbatim). Lumped together with \"Beas and hives trammels\" at single appraised value $391.50; no per-person valuation extractable.",
      "will_probate": "Intestate. Letters of Administration, Monmouth Surrogate File 8480 M, sworn at Freehold 1802-05-29 before Caleb Lloyd, Monmouth County Surrogate; granted to widow Jane (Schenck) Covenhoven and eldest son Elias I. Conover/Covenhoven (b. 1779, age 23 at LOA). $9,812 administration bond same date, payable to Joseph Bloomfield, Esq., Ordinary/Surrogate-General of NJ (then Governor 1801–1812); sureties Daniel Covenhoven (= cp_ens_042 Daniel G., brother per Cocheu #509) and Lewis Gordon (unidentified). Decedent named \"John G. Covenhoven\" on LOA oath sheet but \"John Covenhoven\" (without middle initial) in bond text — consistent with \"G.\" as a father-patronymic used selectively rather than as a fixed middle name. Verbatim LOA + bond text on cp_sou_088.Source_Quotation.",
