      "sources": "PRIMARY: cp_sou_004 (Garetta Cowenhoven Receipt Book 1814-1830, CBH bcms_0095). NYU Special Collections Finding Aid bcms_0095 — Cowenhoven receipt books (https://findingaids.library.nyu.edu/cbh/bcms_0095/); NYC Cemetery Project — Vechte-Cowenhoven Family Burial Ground (https://nycemetery.wordpress.com/2024/09/02/vechte-cowenhoven-family-burial-ground/); cp_per_040 Active row + 1827-11-15 \"Six Cents Reward\" New-York Star runaway-ad citation; cross-referenced w/ cp_ens_008 (spouse) project records.",
      "notes": "Widow of cp_ens_008 (John R. Cowenhoven) from 1811-09-02. Continued enslaving practice into NY's gradual-abolition transition: the 1827-11-15 runaway ad for Maria Philips was filed FOUR MONTHS AFTER NY's general emancipation took effect on 1827-07-04. Maria Philips, born ~1809, would have been a \"term slave\" indentured until age 25 (1834) under the 1799 NY Gradual Abolition Act. The \"Six Cents Reward\" — a token amount, not a real bounty — reads as a perfunctory legal gesture rather than a genuine recovery effort, reflecting an enslaver whose claim was already legally tenuous. Garetta is sister-in-law of Bedford Nicholas Cowenhoven (cp_ens_005). Per memory `project_bedford_nicholas_will_uniqueness.md`, Maria Philips entered her household as a young child (~2) when John R. died in 1811. Receipt book purchased by CBH from The Kelmscott Bookshop in 2019.",
