      "sources": "WikiTree Covenhoven-126 (https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Covenhoven-126); Old Stone House (Brooklyn) — Wikipedia (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Stone_House_(Brooklyn)); Vechte-Cowenhoven Family Burial Ground — NYC Cemetery Project (https://nycemetery.wordpress.com/2024/09/02/vechte-cowenhoven-family-burial-ground/); 1810-01-27 Brooklyn town manumissions — NYC Municipal Archive, Old Town Records Collection: Manumissions of Slaves (https://nycrecords.access.preservica.com/uncategorized/IO_fa92ce85-902d-48b7-bac4-b9e0bfbf2398/); cp_sou_009 — Will and Probate Inventory of his father Rem Cowenhoven (1782-01-12 will / 1783-02-10 inventory; NYHS); Brooklyn Cowenhoven Land Agreements pp.419-426 (three coordinated 1789 indentures with uncle John; cp_sou_### pending mint)",
      "notes": "Bedford Nicholas is — per Chris — the only Cowenhoven so far identified to have manumitted enslaved people through his will. The 'R.' in 'Nicholas R. Cowenhoven' reads as a Rem-son disambiguator; the same convention appears in the 1790 Cortelyou land sale. Burial location uncertain: Chris notes Flatbush Dutch Reformed Church Cemetery; the Vechte-Cowenhoven Family Burial Ground is also possible given the maternal Vechte line and inheritance — pending confirmation. Spouse Catharine Vanderbilt WikiTree cross-link pending (a 1769 PA Vanderbilt-436 surfaced in initial WebSearch but does not match a Brooklyn marriage). | 2026-04-28 update: parcel inheritance from Rem 1782 documented (Roycraft farm + Aughtieste Kamp + Wallabocht meadow + half-share of residue); three coordinated 1789 indentures with uncle John (cp_ens_034) documented (Aughtieste Kamp sale + woodland division + ratification of 1783 sale). Pre-marriage at this time — m. Catharine Vanderbilt 1793-11-14 (Cocheu #651(c) p.84) — so no separate-examination clause appears in his 1789 deeds (unlike brother John R.'s deed which had Garritie's separate examination). | 2026-05-22 cleanup: Cocheu #651(c) p.84 wired (BC/BD); spouse Catharine Vanderbilt minted as cp_fam_336 (Tier-2 Vanderbilt); marriage date corrected 1791 → 1793-11-14 per Cocheu canonical; children_summary bloat replaced ('No issue' per Cocheu); enslaved_people_linked reverse-link gap fixed (added cp_per_145, cp_per_154, cp_per_155, cp_per_197 + cp_rec_015 to match 11 Active AG matches + 1 UNNAMED); confidence_flag=MATCH set.",
      "raw_related_family": "",
      "raw_related_enslavers": "Parent|cp_ens_006; Grandparent|cp_ens_007; Sibling|cp_ens_008; Sibling|cp_fam_055; Sibling|cp_fam_056; Spouse|cp_fam_336; Mother|cp_fam_333",
      "notable_records": "1810-01-27 Brooklyn town manumissions (Nero, Susannah, Harry, James, Sarah) recorded post-mortem from his will; will also manumitted Thomas + Neen (Active rows note 'No record of it taking place'); will assigned funds for the benefit of minors and stipulated guardianship until old enough for a trade; inherited the Vechte-Cortelyou House (today's Old Stone House) from maternal grandfather Claes Van Vechten via 1779 will; sold the house and farm portion to Jacques Cortelyou in 1790 as 'Nicholas R. Cowenhoven.' | 1782-01-12 inheritance from Rem (cp_ens_006, cp_eve_030, cp_sou_009): clause 7 — Roycraft farm (rented to Mr. Ryerson); clause 8 — Aughter-Camp / Aughtieste Kamp ~27 acres; clause 9 — Wallabocht meadow + 2 ac adjoining strip; clause 11 — undivided residue (with brother John R. cp_ens_008) as tenants in common. | 1789-06-30 sale of Aughtieste Kamp (~25 ac as later surveyed) to uncle John Cowenhoven (cp_ens_034) for £50 + 1 acre meadow companion conveyance (Brooklyn Cowenhoven Land Agreements pp.419-421top; cp_sou_### pending mint). Acknowledged 8 July 1789, recorded 1 August 1789 — both before his uncle Judge Nicholas (cp_ens_001). | 1789-05-01 Woodland-division indenture co-grantor with brother John R. + sister-in-law Garritie (Garetta Tiebout cp_ens_025) → uncle John; 38 ac 7 perches Brooklyn + 5.5 ac New Utrecht; 5 shillings + reciprocal woodland (Brooklyn Cowenhoven Land Agreements pp.421-424). | 1789-06-30 Ratification deed: ratified his moiety in brother John R.'s 26 March 1783 sale of 19 ac 1q 33p Brooklyn land to uncle John for £233.10 specie (Brooklyn Cowenhoven Land Agreements pp.425-426). At time of 1783 sale he was a minor (age ~14) under brother John R.'s guardianship; ratified upon attaining majority | EVENT-PID refs: cp_eve_021 (1809-08-01 will) + cp_eve_022 (1810-01-27 Brooklyn town manumissions certificate executed post-mortem).",
