      "residence_primary": "Middlesex County, New Jersey through at least 1795 (son William Emmons Conover b. 1795-01-08 New Brunswick Middlesex per FS KZRB-4NV); 1809 manumission filed at West Windsor Township Middlesex (possibly at family's inherited Penn's Neck plantation per father's 1777 will); later migrated to Milton, Northumberland County, PA (wife buried Milton Cem 1830-11-25; Ruliff buried Milton Cem 1854-12-18)",
      "occupation": "(pending — yeoman presumed; father William #574 was 'yeoman, of Penn's Neck, Middlesex County' per 1777 will)",
      "father_text": "William⁶ Covenhoven (Cocheu 82:4 #574; b. 1742-06-08 d. 1777-10-17, bur. Penn's Neck Cem; 'yeoman, of Penn's Neck, Middlesex County' per 1777 will NJA:34:291; m. 1764-09-08 Deborah Voorhees of Long Island by license NYM:218) — HYPOTHESIS-STRONG pending reconciliation with Cocheu's listing of #574(c) Roeloff⁷ as m. Elizabeth Johnson (vs. FaG-confirmed wife Amy Mary Lake). Three live scenarios: (A) Cocheu wrong on wife name; (B) two distinct Roeloffs/Ruliffs in same generation [unlikely — Cocheu thorough on Penn's Neck]; (C) two wives. Identity-as-manumitter MATCH-grade; parent chain HYPOTHESIS pending primary-source reconciliation.",
      "mother_text": "Deborah Voorhees of Long Island (per Cocheu 82:4 #574 + FS KZV1-X4V) — HYPOTHESIS by inheritance of father-attribution; same caveat as father field.",
      "spouse_text": "Amy Mary Lake (1770-1830-11-25 aged 60y 7m per Milton Cem PA gravestone; FS LHWS-5MF) — m. 2 March 1794 (per FS KCXV-6HK). Both buried jointly Milton Cemetery, Northumberland County, PA.",
      "children_summary": "4 children per FS KCXV-6HK family panel: (1) William Emmons Conover b. 1795-01-08 New Brunswick Middlesex NJ, d. 1852-03-09; m. 7 December 1813 Somerset NJ; 1850 residence North Brunswick Township Middlesex NJ (FS KZRB-4NV; Chris-verified screenshot 2026-05-14); (2) Richard Lake Kovenhoven b. 1797 d. 1861 (FS KH8F-15F); (3) David K. Conover b. 1800 d. Deceased (FS KCCG-L7W); (4) Hannah Covenhoven b. 1802 d. Deceased (FS KZ78-5MH). The Conover/Kovenhoven surname split among the children is the typical anglicization pattern for Middlesex/Mercer Cowenhovens 1795-1810.",
      "is_enslaver": true,
      "evidence_status": "documented",
      "enslaver_link": "cp_ens_068",
      "sources": "PRIMARY: Find A Grave memorial 107977825 (Ruliff (Ralph) Kovenhoven, Milton Cemetery, Milton, Northumberland Co., PA; gravestone photo by Barry Keefer). PRIMARY: gravestone inscription 'R.K. Died Dec 18 1854 Aged 85 Years' + 'Amy ... died Nov 25 1830 Aged 60 yrs 7 mo'. PRIMARY-by-inheritance: Cocheu, Lincoln C. 'The Van Kouwenhoven-Conover Family.' NYG&BR vol. LXXXII, no. 4 (October 1951): #574 (cp_sou_057) — father William⁶ + son 'Roeloff⁷ m. Elizabeth Johnson' enumeration (parent-chain HYPOTHESIS source). PRIMARY-by-inheritance: William⁶ #574's will dated 1777-10-07 / proved 1778-05-30 (NJA:34:291). FS profile KCXV-6HK (b/d/spouse). FS profile KZRB-4NV (son William Emmons Conover, b. 1795-01-08 New Brunswick Middlesex NJ). Active R196 + Active source URL ark 3:1:3Q9M-CSGD-7SJS-V (1809 manumission of Will at West Windsor).",
      "notes": "MINTED 2026-05-14 from Chris-shared FaG screenshot (memorial 107977825) + FS KCXV-6HK profile + FS KZRB-4NV son's record + Cocheu 82:4 #574 contextual lineage.\n\nIDENTITY-AS-MANUMITTER = MATCH-grade. Evidence chain:\n- FaG primary: gravestone Milton Cem PA, 'died Dec 18 1854 aged 85' (= b. ~1769) plus joint burial with wife Amy 'died Nov 25 1830 aged 60' (= b. ~1770). The gravestone documents existence, dates, and marriage.\n- FS KCXV-6HK header: b. 18 Dec 1769 Middlesex County NJ.\n- Son's birthplace anchor: William Emmons Conover b. 1795-01-08 New Brunswick Middlesex (FS KZRB-4NV) — primary documentation of Ruliff's continuous Middlesex NJ residence 1769→1795+.\n- Age 40 in 1809 at the West Windsor manumission — prime adult age.\n- No competing Ruliff/Roelef Cowenhoven candidate documented in Middlesex County in 1809.\n\nPARENT CHAIN = HYPOTHESIS-STRONG (not MATCH). Two threads in conflict:\n- FS attaches KCXV-6HK to William Covenhoven KHCQ-VS7 (= Cocheu's #574, b. 1742-06-08 d. 1777-10-17, Penn's Neck yeoman) + Deborah Voorhees. Chris flagged the attached source on KCXV-6HK as 'conflicting / wrong-looking' (2026-05-14 question response).\n- Cocheu 82:4 #574(c) lists William #574's 'another son Roeloff' (from father's 1777 will text) as 'Roeloff⁷ b. — m. Elizabeth Johnson' (no other detail). The 'Elizabeth Johnson' wife is at odds with FaG-buried wife Amy Mary Lake.\n- Three scenarios live: (A) Cocheu wrong on wife name — same person; (B) two distinct Roeloffs/Ruliffs in same generation — unlikely given Cocheu thoroughness; (C) two wives — possible if Elizabeth Johnson was an early marriage that ended in death. Reconciliation pending.\n\nFAMILY GEOGRAPHIC ARC:\n- Born 1769-12-18 in Middlesex County NJ — father William #574 was 'of Penn's Neck' per 1777 will, so birth likely Penn's Neck (West Windsor Township) area.\n- Father died 1777-10-17 when Ruliff was age 7-8. Mother Deborah Voorhees (widow) had use of plantation until eldest son William⁷ was 21 (1788).\n- Family appears to have shifted from southern Middlesex (Penn's Neck) to northern Middlesex (New Brunswick) by 1795 (son William Emmons's birth). Possible: widow Deborah moved closer to Voorhees kin in New Brunswick area after husband's death.\n- 1809-02-18: Ruliff manumitted Will at West Windsor — filed at the township where family's inherited Penn's Neck plantation sat.\n- Later migration to Milton, Northumberland County, PA (post-1810; wife buried Milton 1830).\n\nFOLLOW-UP:\n- Reconcile Cocheu's #574(c) 'Elizabeth Johnson' wife with FaG-documented Amy Mary Lake. Possible sources: NJ marriage records 1794 (Ruliff + Amy Lake) or earlier (if Elizabeth Johnson existed); FS sources panels for KCXV-6HK and his children.\n- Establish whether brother William⁷ #574(b) b. 1767-12-02 m. Mary Grover (d. 1838) was also an enslaver — same Penn's Neck cluster, also still alive in 1809, distinct from cp_ens_054.\n- Eventually mint William⁶ #574 as a cp_fam_NNN row (currently only text inside cp_fam_141's children_summary; needs his own row for the broader cp_fam_141 descent pass).",
      "raw_related_family": "",
      "raw_related_enslavers": "Grandparent|cp_fam_141 (William Willemse Kowenhoven of NJ, Cocheu #183; FS L1HS-3PF); Grandparent|cp_fam_188 (Margaret Schenck, Cocheu #234; FS M5BR-XRL); Great-grandparent|cp_fam_054 (Willem Willemse Kowenhoven); Great-great-grandparent|cp_fam_007 (Willem Gerritsz Couwenhoven); 2nd-cousin-once-removed|cp_ens_054 (William Covenhoven of West Windsor — same Penn's Neck cluster via parallel descent from cp_fam_007 through cp_fam_057 vs. cp_fam_054); Father's-uncle|cp_fam_058 (William Jansen Van Couwenhoven of Penn's Neck — Cocheu #168, the founder of the Penn's Neck cluster via cp_fam_057 line);Father|cp_ens_060",
      "notable_records": "(1) cp_per_196 Will, age 37, manumitted 1809-02-18 at West Windsor Township, Middlesex County, NJ (Active R196; source = FS ark 3:1:3Q9M-CSGD-7SJS-V). (2) Milton Cemetery joint gravestone with wife Amy (FaG memorial 107977825).",
