      "sources": "PRIMARY: Runaway ad for Harry, by William Conover, \"Forty Dollars Reward,\" True American (Trenton, NJ), April 14, 1801, p. 3. PRIMARY: NJ Supreme Court Case Files, 1704-1844, Case No. 34538* (cp_sou_040; cp_eve_148). PRIMARY: Will of Harmen Covenhoven of West Windsor, Middlesex Co. NJ, dated 1803-11-21 (probate location pending). EXTERNAL: New Jersey Slavery Records, William Conover NJS-PER-02451 https://records.njslavery.org/s/doc/item/7169 (curated by Princeton & Slavery Project / Indy Davis). EXTERNAL: New Jersey Slavery Records, 1801-04-04 Freedom seeking: Harry, NJS-EVE-01030 https://records.njslavery.org/s/doc/item/7352. PENDING: WikiTree profile, FamilySearch ID, Find a Grave memorial, primary baptism + death records, spouse + children records.\n\nCocheu, Lincoln C. \"The Van Kouwenhoven-Conover Family.\" NYG&BR vol. LXXXII, no. 3 (July 1951): #541(h) (cp_sou_056) — primary citation establishing father chain via Hermanus.",
      "notes": "MINTED 2026-05-08 PHASE 3B per Chris approval. Defendant in 1814 NJ Supreme Court Case 34538* (Phebe + Eliza Habeas Corpus, cp_eve_148). Identification anchored by: (a) RESIDENCE — Active R185 col Z reads 'William Covenhoven of West Windsor, Middlesex County, NJ' for the 1814 HC defendant; (b) PRIOR HISTORY — same name + same county appears in 1801 True American newspaper runaway ad (NJ Slavery Records NJS-PER-02451) for an enslaved man Harry, signed 'WILLIAM CONOVER' from 'near Princeton, in Middlesex county' — West Windsor sat adjacent to Princeton in Middlesex Co. 1801-1838; (c) KINSHIP — father Harmen Covenhoven of West Windsor's 1803-11-21 will named this William as co-executor alongside son-in-law Cornelius Covenhoven, establishing him as a propertied West Windsor adult by 1803. DISTINCT FROM other minted Williams: cp_ens_011 William Albertse (d. 1790-03-19); cp_ens_012 William Jr. of Freehold (d. ~1810); cp_ens_026 William Kouwenhoven of Flatlands NY; cp_ens_052 William W. Covenhoven Jr. of South Brunswick (different Middlesex township). Confidence: HYPOTHESIS-STRONG. Vital dates (birth, death, spouse, children) and WikiTree/FS/FaG anchors PENDING. Possible father Harmen also a cp_ens mint candidate (1803 will mentions wife and children; enslavement footprint of Harmen unknown). COINCIDENCE note: Harmen's wife was named Phoebe (white); the enslaved Phebe in this William's 1814 HC case is a DIFFERENT person (Black woman of Middlesex Co.).\n\n2026-05-08 BACKFILL: Harry (cp_per_129) was already minted in our Active sheet (R123 Disappearance/Runaway 1801-04-14, source URL pointing at NJ Slavery Records NJS-EVE-01030) — missed in Phase 3B initial assessment. Wired this session: cp_eve_149 (Disappearance) + cp_sou_041 (True American Apr 14 1801 ad). Active R123 backfilled cols Q/U/V/AG/AH. cp_per_129 = MATCH attribution since the runaway ad explicitly names William Conover as enslaver and cp_ens_054 is the only William Conover documented in West Windsor / near-Princeton Middlesex Co. for this period.\n\n[2026-05-10 STAGE 3c] **Father chain resolved + identity MATCH-confirmed**. Cocheu 82:3 #541(h) (cp_sou_056) supplies birth 1781-10-31 + spouse Catharine Van Voorhees m. 1802-02-02 + father=Hermanus #541 (= newly minted cp_ens_058 in Stage 3b). Full chain: Wolphert > Gerrit > Willem (cp_fam_007) > John (cp_fam_057) > William of Penn's Neck (cp_fam_058) > Hermanus (cp_ens_058) > **William of West Windsor (cp_ens_054, this row)**. Identity now MATCH-grade beyond just the 1814 HC defendant residence anchor.",
