      "spouse_text": "Cornelia Wyckoff (1786-1851, FS L638-94R) — m. 1805-01-24 Long Island NY (per FS L638-9HN family group). **THIRD KOUWENHOVEN-WYCKOFF MARRIAGE in this family** — cp_ens_026 William m. Annatie Wyckoff 1778; cp_ens_028 uncle Luke m. Ann Wyckoff 1790; this row m. Cornelia Wyckoff 1805. Possibly endogamous: Cornelia could be Annatie's niece or cousin; warrants follow-up via FS L638-94R parents pull.",
      "children_summary": "2 children per FS L638-9HN family group (Chris-shared screenshot 2026-04-26 PM): (1) William G. Kouwenhoven (1806-Deceased, FS 9HNM-4JM) — eldest son; 'G.' middle initial = Garret-son patronymic, parallel to 'R.' = Rem-son in cp_ens_005/008; (2) Joanna W. De Bevoise (1818-1900, FS PZP3-D6C) — daughter; surname De Bevoise indicates marriage to a De Bevoise; 'W.' middle initial possibly Wyckoff-mother patronymic.",
      "is_enslaver": true,
      "evidence_status": "documented",
      "enslaver_link": "cp_ens_029",
      "sources": "FamilySearch L638-9HN family group panel (spouse Cornelia Wyckoff L638-94R, 2 children, parents cp_ens_026/Annatie Wyckoff with marriage 1778-12-12 Flatlands) — Chris-shared screenshot 2026-04-26 PM. FamilySearch L6MR-8DT 14-children panel (cp_ens_026 William's children, used for sibling-block disambiguation) — Chris-shared screenshot 2026-04-26 PM. Town of Flatlands birth-indenture register entries 1815-1817 (NYC Municipal Archives, Brooklyn Old Town Records, Flatlands) for the 6 MATCH enslaved persons.",
      "notes": "STUB MINT 2026-04-26 PM via FS L638-9HN family group screenshot (Chris) + cp_ens_026 L6MR-8DT 14-children FS pull (same date). Identity confirmed via narrowing process: of cp_ens_026 William's 14 children, only Garret 1783-1823 is name-compatible AND age-compatible (32-34 yrs old in 1815-1817) for the Town Clerk Gerrit role; Johanes W. (1794), Peter (1799), George Van (1809) are wrong-name and too-young respectively. **Memorial-naming layers:** named after deceased older brother Garret #1 1780-1780 (LC5K-H1Z) AND, after 1784, also a memorial-namesake for deceased uncle Garret LCM3-7G7 (1761-1784). **Wyckoff-marriage triple-iteration** within this Flatlands branch (William 1778, Luke 1790, Garret 1805) suggests endogamous kin-network; worth a Wyckoff-side genealogy follow-up. **Lineage:** cp_fam_007 → cp_fam_054 → cp_ens_027 → cp_ens_026 → cp_ens_029 (this row); 4-generation Flatlands-staying spine. **Open questions:** (1) Who succeeded Garret as Flatlands Town Clerk after 1817? (2) Did Garret's widow Cornelia file any post-1827 manumissions? (3) Did son William G. (1806-Deceased) reach adulthood? — daughter Joanna m. De Bevoise lived to 1900, suggesting a continuing line. (4) Does Garret appear in any 1820 federal census as Flatlands head of household? (5) Cornelia Wyckoff = Annatie Wyckoff's niece/cousin? (6) Probate inventory at Garret's 1823 death — would name any enslaved persons in his estate.",
      "raw_related_family": "",
      "raw_related_enslavers": "Parent|cp_ens_026",
      "notable_records": "TOWN CLERK OF FLATLANDS 1815-1817 — per BOTR-Flatlands birth register entries naming 'Gerrit Kouwenhoven Town Clerk' as enslaver across 6 enslaved persons in the 1815-1817 window: cp_per_026 Bet, cp_per_027 Eve, cp_per_030 Benjamin, cp_per_035 Adam, cp_per_036 Frank, cp_per_037 Tom (NYC Municipal Archives, Brooklyn Old Town Records, Flatlands; SOURCE-BOTR-Flatlands-Birth_Registers_and_Manumissions_of_Enslaved_People; https://nycrecords.access.preservica.com/uncategorized/IO_c48e45ec-2ae4-43a5-99dd-71a0e3fdb085/). 1805-01-24 Marriage to Cornelia Wyckoff at Long Island, NY (per FS L638-9HN family group). 1820/1830 census continuity: Garret would appear as Flatlands head of household 1820 (age 37); pending census image pull. Died 1823 = before NY general emancipation 1827; surviving widow Cornelia (d.1851) would have inherited the household + any term-slave or enslaved persons at that point.",
      "enslaved_people_linked": "**6 MATCH (BOTR-Flatlands birth register Town Clerk 1815-1817 attribution, mapped 2026-04-26 PM):** cp_per_026 Bet, cp_per_027 Eve, cp_per_030 Benjamin, cp_per_035 Adam, cp_per_036 Frank, cp_per_037 Tom. Garret was in office during the peak filing window of the 1799 NY gradual emancipation Act, just like his father cp_ens_026 — his role as enslaver-officiant on his own indenture filings parallels the cp_ens_026 1800-1808 pattern (a Town Clerk filing entries on his own enslaved household).",
