      "enslaver_link": "cp_ens_039",
      "sources": "Find A Grave Memorial #177364299: https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/177364299/john-i-covenhoven; WikiTree profile Conover-140: https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Conover-140; Genealogical Society of New Jersey, Genealogies of New Jersey Families, From the Genealogical Magazine of New Jersey (2 Vols.) (Baltimore: Genealogical Publishing Co., 1996), 1:419 — Albert L. Stokes, 'Some Johnson Descendants of Jan Willemszen Van der Loosdrecht'; Brouwer Genealogy Database (referenced in Find A Grave bio); PRIMARY: cp_sou_016 Slave Manumissions, 1787-1844, Monmouth County, NJ — Manumission Book pp.116, 128.",
      "notes": "MINTED 2026-05-05 PM (this session). Identification anchored by Chris's 5/5 cross-reference to Find A Grave Memorial #177364299 + WikiTree Conover-140 + Genealogical Society of NJ Vol 1:419. Two-record evidence chain (cp_eve_080 1823 + cp_eve_081 1832) confirms same enslaver across both records via consistent 'I.' patronymic + Township-of-Freehold residence + Conover/Covenhoven orthographic variant pattern. Militia 'Col.' rank inferred from 1832 deed style; rank acquired sometime between 1823-12-09 and 1832-02-28. Burial at Old Tennent Churchyard, Manalapan, Monmouth County, NJ (Find A Grave). Death date unknown.",
      "raw_related_family": "",
      "raw_related_enslavers": "Possible kin to cp_ens_020 Col. John Covenhoven of Freehold (Rev War colonel, DAR # A026770, estate inventory 1803). OPEN HYPOTHESIS — John I. Covenhoven's biological father per Find A Grave is John P. Covenhoven (b. 23 Mar 1740, d. 24 Dec 1811), whose 1811 death year does NOT match cp_ens_020's ~1803 inventory. So John P. ≠ cp_ens_020 unless cp_ens_020's death year is mis-attributed. Possible alternatives: (a) John P. is a kinsman (brother/cousin) of cp_ens_020; (b) cp_ens_020 = John P., and the 1803 inventory refers to a different event (not death). Verify via Old Tennent Churchyard records, Brouwer Genealogy Database, or Genealogical Society of NJ Vol 1:419 (Stokes).",
      "notable_records": "cp_eve_080 — 1823-12-09 manumission of Pompy Grandin (cp_per_071), age ~35, in Township of Freehold, Monmouth County, before Overseers Joseph + Lewis Gordon and Justices John Hull + James G. Herbert. Manumission Book p.116. PARTIAL — deed body continuation pending. cp_eve_081 — 1832-02-28 SALE: bought the indenture of William Miller (cp_per_076), a Black boy ~12 years old, from Daniel L. Dey of Middlesex County for $100 for the remaining 9-year term. Manumission Book p.128. Project event_type = Sale (Enslaved.org CV); subject role = Indentured Person. New project event-subtype 'Sale of Indentured Person' surfaced via this record.",
